ign ==\nThe iPhone SE features a design with an aluminum frame, and its front and back are made out of glass. The phone's dimensions are identical to that of the iPhone 8, and the external design is the same except for a centered Apple logo and no iPhone branding. It features bezels on the top and bottom of the front and a home button integrated with second-generation [[Touch ID]].<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-se/ |title = iPhone SE 2020: Everything We Know |website = MacRumors |language = en |access-date = April 15, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180805112853/https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-se/ |archive-date = August 5, 2018 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone SE is available in three colors \u2014 white, black,<!-- colors are not proper nouns --> and [[Product Red|(Product) Red]].<ref name=\"Official website: specifications /> Where this iPhone does deviate from the iPhone 8's design is with respect to the white model. Unlike the silver iPhone 8 (and all prior silver iPhones since the [[iPhone 4]]), the white iPhone SE features black bezels like the black models and red models, in line with the color schemes of the [[iPhone 11 Pro]] and [[iPhone XR]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Color !!Name      <!-- hex codes from product selection page -->\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#1F2020\"| ||Black \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"F9F6EF\" |  ||White \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#BA0C2E\"  |  ||Product Red\n|}\n\n== Specifications ==\n\n===Hardware===\nThe iPhone SE incorporates the Apple A13 Bionic system-on-chip (SoC) with an [[Apple motion coprocessors|M13 motion coprocessor]]. It is available in three internal storage configurations; 64&nbsp;GB, 128&nbsp;GB and 256&nbsp;GB.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" /> The SE has a rating of IP67 under [[IP Code|IEC standard 60529]] for dust and water resistance.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" /> \n\n==== Display ====\nThe iPhone SE features the same Retina HD display found on the iPhone 8. However, [[Force Touch|3D Touch]] is replaced by Haptic Touch.\n\n==== Camera ====\nThe iPhone SE features a single 12 MP rear camera similar to the wide camera of iPhone 11 and iPhone 11 Pro. The camera has a <!-- MOS:NOSYMBOLS -->f/1.8 aperture, autofocus, optical image stabilization, and a quad-LED True Tone flash. It is capable of recording 4K video at 24&nbsp;fps, 30&nbsp;fps, or 60&nbsp;fps, 1080p HD video at 30&nbsp;fps or 60&nbsp;fps, or 720p HD video at 30&nbsp;fps. The phone can also take panoramas up to 63&nbsp;MP, and is capable of shooting photos in burst mode.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" />\n\nThe front camera of the iPhone SE is a 7&nbsp;MP camera with f/2.2 aperture and autofocus, capable of shooting 1080p HD video at 30 fps.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" />\n\nBoth the front and rear cameras of the iPhone SE support Smart HDR, Portrait mode and Portrait Lighting.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" /> Unlike the iPhone 11 and 11 Pro, iPhone SE does not support Night mode.\n\n===Software===\nThe iPhone SE ships with [[iOS]] [[iOS 13|13]] and supports [[Apple Pay]].<!-- Apple Card is implicit with Apple Pay. --><ref name=\"Official website: specifications />\n\n== Timeline of iPhone models ==\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|iPhone SE (2020)}}\n* {{Official site|https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/}}\n\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc. hardware}}\n{{Apple}}\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2020]]\n[[Category:iOS]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2020]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications]]\n", "name_user": "Prahlad balaji", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCamera:fix improper capitalization", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPhone_SE_(2nd_generation)"}
{"title_page": "Giffnock", "text_new": "{{short description|Townin East Renfrewshire, Scotland}}\n{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|static_image_name = Giffnock, East Renfrewshire. - geograph.org.uk - 429703.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Shops on Fenwick Road\n|country              = Scotland\n|official_name        = Giffnock\n|gaelic_name          = Giofnag<ref name=GaelicName/>\n|scots_name           = Giffnock<ref name=RailwayNames>{{cite web|title=List of Railway station names |url=http://newsnetscotland.com/index.php/component/content/article/2999-list-of-railway-station-names.html |accessdate=20 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130122064223/http://newsnetscotland.com/index.php/component/content/article/2999-list-of-railway-station-names.html |archivedate=22 January 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> \n|population= 16,178\n|population_ref= ([[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 Census]])\n|os_grid_reference    = NS565585\n|coordinates          = {{coord|55.805109|-4.294610 |display=inline,title}}\n|map_type             = Scotland\n| pushpin_map             = Scotland East Renfrewshire#Scotland Glasgow\n|lieutenancy_scotland = [[Renfrewshire (historic)|Renfrewshire]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[East Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Renfrewshire]]\n|constituency_scottish_parliament = [[Eastwood (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Eastwood]]\n|post_town            = GLASGOW\n|postcode_district    = G46\n|postcode_area        = G\n|dial_code            = 0141\n|edinburgh_distance= {{convert|51|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[Boxing the compass|ENE]]\n|london_distance= {{convert|344|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[Boxing the compass|SSE]]\n }}\n'''Giffnock ''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u026a|f|n|\u0259|k}}; {{lang-sco|Giffnock}}; {{lang-gd|Giofnag}}, {{IPA-gd|\u02c8k\u02b2ifnak|pron}}) is an affluent suburban town and the administrative centre of [[East Renfrewshire]] in the [[Central Lowlands]] of [[Scotland]]. It lies {{convert|3.7|mi|km|1}} east of [[Barrhead]], {{convert|5.6|mi|km|1}} east-southeast of [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] and {{convert|5.3|mi|km|1}} northwest of [[East Kilbride]], at the southwest of the [[Greater Glasgow|Greater Glasgow conurbation]]. Giffnock is mentioned in documents as early as the seventeenth century as a scattered agricultural settlement. In the late eighteenth century, [[Archibald Montgomerie, 11th Earl of Eglinton|Archibald Montgomerie]], the [[Earl of Eglinton]], was forced to partition the land into a number of smaller properties.\n\nThe urbanisation and development of Giffnock began in the mid to late nineteenth century with the construction of several sandstone [[Quarry|quarries]], and this prompted the development of the first railway link with nearby Glasgow. Large-scale quarrying continued in Giffnock for almost a century. However, the quarrying ceased by the 1920s, and other uses were found for the quarries. An additional railway service began at the start of the twentieth century, closely followed by the arrival of [[Glasgow Corporation Tramways]]. Giffnock's relative closeness to Glasgow coupled with the local industry and good transports links helped it to develop into a suburban town, as many wealthy merchants chose to construct villas in its smog-free environs and commute daily to the city. \n \nAlthough heavy industry died out in the area during the early twentieth century, as part of Scotland's densely populated [[Central Belt]], Giffnock has continued to grow as a [[Commuter town|dormitory town]], supported by its position within the Greater Glasgow area, from roughly 1,425 residents in the early twentieth century to 16,178 in 2001. Expansion continues due to several new housing developments; however, much of the land is now urbanised or designated [[park]]land, leaving little room for further expansion.\n\n==History==\nThe [[Scottish Gaelic language|Scottish Gaelic]] name for Giffnock is Giofnag<ref name=GaelicName>{{cite web|title=Giffnock|url=http://www.gaelicplacenames.org/databasedetails.php?id=383|work=Gaelic Place-names of Scotland|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> and is of partially [[Common Brittonic|Brythonic]] and [[Scottish Gaelic|Gaelic]] origin. 'Cefn' (i.e. 'Giff') comes from the Brythonic meaning 'ridge' and the Gaelic ''cnoc'' (i.e. 'nock') meaning \"hill\". In Gaelic, ''oc'' or ''og'' is a [[diminutive]], and thus when added to ''cefn'' gives Giffnock the meaning of \"Little Ridge\".<ref name=STS2/>\n\nThe first written mention of Giffnock came in 1530, when [[James V of Scotland|James V]] presented Rockend (Ruken) Mill and the surrounding lands to [[Hugh Montgomerie, 1st Earl of Eglinton]].<ref name=CAA/>\nThe settlement of Giffnock first appeared as Gisnock, in an atlas created by [[Dutch people|Dutch]] [[cartographer]] [[Joan Blaeu]] in 1654, the first atlas of Scotland.<ref name=STS2>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=2}}</ref> Giffnock was primarily a scattered farming community until the late 1780s, when [[Archibald Montgomerie, 11th Earl of Eglinton]] was forced to partition the land into a number of small properties for sale to raise finances.<ref name=BBCGiffnock>{{cite web|title=BBC Scotland \u2013 Giffnock (East Renfrewshire)|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/landscapes/giffnock/|work=landscapes|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Industry===\nIn 1835, the first [[sandstone]] [[quarry]] in Giffnock opened. Before long, the town became known for this industry, and at its peak, there were four quarries in Giffnock, three surface quarries and one underground quarry, which together employed over 1,000 men.<ref name=CAA/><ref name=Quarries>{{cite web|title=Quarries \u2013 Portal to the Past|url=http://www.portaltothepast.co.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3210|work=Portal to the Past|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> The quarries produced two types of sandstone: \"liver rock\" and \"moor rock\". \"Liver rock\" was particularly popular with masons thanks to its lack of [[Stratum|stratification]], which made the stone easy to work with. In 1854, a coal mining firm managed by civil engineers [[Hugh Baird (engineer)|Hugh Baird]] and [[Robert Stevenson (civil engineer)|Robert Stevenson]] took over the running of the quarries and by 1866 the [[Glasgow South Western Line|Busby Railway]] was built, allowing them to transport the stone by rail.<ref name=Quarries/><ref>{{cite web|title=Busby Railway|url=http://www.railbrit.co.uk/Busby_Railway/frame.htm|work=RailBrit|publisher=RailBrit|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref>  Originally, a lower level line was laid from [[Giffnock railway station]] into the Orchard Quarry to facilitate the extraction of the stone.<ref name=STS5>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=5}}</ref>\n\nSandstone from the Giffnock quarries was primarily used within the nearby city of [[Glasgow]] and can be found in older parts of the [[University of Glasgow]] and the interior of [[Kelvingrove Art Gallery]].<ref name=Quarries/> A small amount of trade was done with Belfast, and some of the finer \"liver rock\" was even transported as far as America and South Africa to build both buildings and monuments.<ref name=STS5/>\n\nQuarrying in Giffnock continued until 1912 when, due to flooding and the high cost of extracting stone, work ceased. Numerous ventures tried to revitalise the quarries for other purposes, including the cultivation of [[mushroom]]s in the tunnels. As the pits began to fill with water, it became an issue that needed to be resolved. In the early 1930s, [[William Beardmore and Company|William Bearmore & Co]] began tipping [[slag]] from the production of steel into the Giffnock quarries.<ref name=STS6>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=6}}</ref> The slag tipping continued until 1969, when Derek Crouch Limited began scrap metal extraction, which lasted until the late 1970s. Today the ground is a wasteland.<ref name=STS7>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=7}}</ref>\n\nCoal mining was also carried out in Giffnock, between 1850 and 1926. The coal produced was of a very poor quality and was of little value to householders. The main use of Giffnock coal was with commercial and industrial customers such as Busby [[History of manufactured gas|Gas Works]].<ref name=STS8>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=8}}</ref>\n\n===Urbanisation and expansion===\nThe opening of [[Giffnock railway station]] in 1866 allowed business people to build sandstone villas and commute daily to the city. At the time, it was much more desirable to live in Giffnock than to live in the smog-polluted city.<ref name=\"STS10\">{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=10}}</ref> By the early 1890s, residential Giffnock began to grow around the railway station and Eastwood Toll,<ref name=Timeline>{{cite web|title=Timeline \u2013 Giffnock|url=http://www.portaltothepast.co.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3290|work=Portal to the past|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> and by 1892 gas was introduced to the area.<ref name=Timeline/> [[Gas lighting|Gas street lamps]] were erected by Busby and District Gas Company in 1893; however, these were supported by a voluntary subscription that many households refused to pay, leaving many areas unlit. It was not until October 1896, when Eastwood Parish Council took over street lighting, that the area was consistently lit at night.<ref name=\"STS13\"/>\n\nIn 1903, a second railway station was opened in Giffnock, [[Whitecraigs railway station]].<ref name=\"butt248\"/> The station lay on the [[Lanarkshire and Ayrshire Railway]], originally built to provide a through route from the [[Lanarkshire]] coalfields to ports such as [[Ardrossan]] on the [[Ayrshire]] coast.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lanarkshire and Ayrshire Railway|url=http://www.railbrit.co.uk/Lanarkshire_and_Ayrshire_Railway/frame.htm|publisher=RailBrit|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe growth of Giffnock was furthered in 1905 by the arrival of the first [[Glasgow Corporation Tramways]] tram in the town.<ref name=Timeline/> The addition of this tram link and the nearby Whitecraigs railway station helped the popularity of Giffnock as a weekend destination and lead to the opening of [[Rouken Glen]] park in 1906 by Archibald Corbett (later Lord Rowallan), the M.P. for Tradeston.<ref name=Timeline/> The Giffnock tramline was one of Glasgow Corporation Tramways's most profitable routes; up to 15,000 travelled to Giffnock on a Sunday to visit Rouken Glen.<ref name=\"STS13\"/>\n\nDuring the great housing boom of the late 1930s, Giffnock began to grow rapidly. Between 1930 and 1940, as many as 3,000 dwellings were constructed, and the population rose dramatically, from 1,425 to 3,471 in 1939 and 9,144 in 1951.<ref name=STS15/>\n\n[[File:Rudolf Hess - Bf 110D Werk Nr 3869 - Wreckage - Bonnyton Moor.jpg|thumb|left|alt=The wreckage of [[Rudolf Hess|Hess's]] [[Messerschmitt Bf 110|Bf 110]]\n crashed in a busby field]]\nOn 7 May 1941, during the [[Greenock Blitz]] of [[World War II]], the [[Nazi German]] [[Luftwaffe]] dropped a group of bombs over Giffnock, but only two houses were destroyed.<ref name=CAA/> \nOn 10 May 1941, [[Rudolf Hess]], a prominent Nazi politician and [[Deputy F\u00fchrer|deputy]] to [[Adolf Hitler]] parachuted out of his [[Messerschmitt Bf 110D]] near [[Waterfoot, East Renfrewshire|Waterfoot]].<ref name=McRoberts>{{cite book | last = McRoberts | first = Douglas | title = Lions Rampant: The Story of 602 Spitfire Squadron | publisher = William Kimber | series =  | edition = | year = 1985 | page = 143 | url = | id = | isbn = 0-7183-0572-8 | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> Hess had flown solo to Scotland in an attempt to negotiate peace with the United Kingdom. He was detained by the [[Home Guard (United Kingdom)|Home Guard]] in the battalion headquarters in the Giffnock Scout hall, where he was questioned by Major Donald, the Assistant Group Officer of the [[Royal Observer Corps|Glasgow Royal Observer Corps]] before being transferred to [[Maryhill Barracks]] in Glasgow the following day. The wreckage of Hess's aircraft was salvaged by 63 Maintenance Unit (MU) between 11 and 16 May 1941.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yourarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk/index.php?title=Hess,_Rudolf_%281894-1987%29_German_Politician |title=National Archives (UK), A2A, AIR 29/1019 |publisher=Yourarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=7 August 2013 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Part of the aeroplane is now in London's [[Imperial War Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airmuseumsuk.org/museum/IWMLondon/index.htm |title=Imperial War Museum London: Aircraft Collection|website= airmuseumsuk.org|accessdate= 10 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nProposals were put forward in 2008 to expand the town with the building of 178 houses on Braidbar Quarries next to Huntly Park, involving the Park closing for a period of two years. However, following 2,000 objections from local people and the opposition of the Scottish Government's reporter, East Renfrewshire Council abandoned the plans in October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Braidbar quarry housing and remediation plans announcement|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3048|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Governance==\n{{see also|History of local government in Scotland}}\nGiffnock is represented by several tiers of elected government. Giffnock Community Council forms the lowest tier of governance whose statutory role is to communicate local opinion to local and central government.<ref name=\"Giffnock Council\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1871|title=Community Councils|date=|accessdate=19 December 2012|author=East Renfrewshire Council|publisher=eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk}}</ref> It is one of ten [[List of community council areas in Scotland|community councils]] of the [[East Renfrewshire]] [[council area]].<ref name=\"Giffnock Council\"/>\n\nEast Renfrewshire Council, the unitary [[Local government in Scotland|local council]], is based in Giffnock and is the Executive, [[Deliberation|deliberative]] and [[legislative]] body responsible for [[Local government in Scotland|local governance]]. The [[Scottish Parliament]] is responsible for [[Devolution|devolved matters]] such as [[Education in Scotland|education]], [[Health in Scotland|health]] and [[Scots law|justice]],<ref name=\"devolved matters\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotlandoffice.gov.uk/what-we-do/reserved-and-devolved-matters.html |title=Reserved and devolved matters |publisher=Scotland Office |accessdate=19 December 2012|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061004074305/http://www.scotlandoffice.gov.uk/what-we-do/reserved-and-devolved-matters.html |archivedate = 4 October 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> while [[reserved and excepted matters|reserved matters]] are dealt with by the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]].\n\nGiffnock forms part of the [[United Kingdom constituencies|county constituency]] of [[East Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Renfrewshire]], electing one member of parliament (MP) to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] of the Parliament of the United Kingdom. [[Kirsten Oswald]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/kirsten-oswald/4413 |publisher=United Kingdom Parliament|title=Kirsten Oswald MP|accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref> of the [[Scottish National Party|SNP]] was elected as MP for East Renfrewshire in the [[List of MPs for constituencies in Scotland 2015\u201317|2015 General Election]]. Before the constituency's creation in 2005, Giffnock lay in the [[Eastwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Eastwood Constituency]]. For the purposes of the [[Scottish Parliament]], Giffnock forms part of the [[Eastwood (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Eastwood Constituency]], which is represented by [[Jackson Carlaw]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]], of the [[Scottish Conservative Party]].\n\n==Geography==\n{{Geographic Location\n|title = '''Neighbouring towns, villages and places.'''\n|Northwest = [[Thornliebank]]\n|North = [[Shawlands]]\n|Northeast = [[Muirend]]\n|West = [[Darnley]]\n|Centre = Giffnock\n|East = [[Castlemilk]]\n|Southwest = [[Newton Mearns]]\n|South = [[Waterfoot, East Renfrewshire|Waterfoot]]\n|Southeast = [[Clarkston, East Renfrewshire|Clarkston]]\n}}\n\n{{climate chart\n| [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]]\n|1.8|6.9|148.2\n|1.8|7.4|104.9\n|3.0|9.6|112.3\n|4.8|12.6|63.6\n|7.3|15.9|67.5\n|10.1|18.1|66.4\n|12.0|19.7|73.0\n|11.7|19.2|92.5\n|9.7|16.4|112.5\n|6.7|12.7|143.1\n|4.0|9.4|126.4\n|1.7|6.9|135.2\n|float=right\n|clear=both\n|source=[http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19812010/sites/paisley.html Met Office]\n}}\n\nAt {{coord|55|48|9|N|4|17|43|W|type:city}} (55.803\u00b0, \u22124.30\u00b0) Giffnock is situated in Scotland's [[Central Lowlands]]. The town lies {{convert|3.7|mi|km|1}} east of [[Barrhead]], {{convert|5.3|mi|km|1}} northwest of [[East Kilbride]] and {{convert|4.3|mi|km|1}} south-southwest of Glasgow. \nThe territory of Giffnock is contiguous with Glasgow and forms part of [[Greater Glasgow]], the [[List of conurbations in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom's fifth largest conurbation]].\n\nGiffnock is situated on the [[plateau]] that encircles Glasgow. It is at edge of the area that defines the basin that Glasgow has developed within.<ref name=CAA>{{cite web|last=Cahill|first=Andrew J|title=Conservation Area Appraisal \u2013 Giffnock|format=PDF|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=8424&p=0|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> \nThe underlay is composed mainly of sedimentary rocks and [[Freestone (masonry)|freestone]] from the Strathclyde and Clackmannan groups of early to mid [[Carboniferous]] age (354 to 316 million years).<ref name=CAA/> \nThe relatively soft and easily eroded rocks have resulted in the landform in the area being mostly flat with gentle undulations.<ref name=CAA/>\nThe area of Giffnock is typically around {{convert|45|m|ft}} to {{convert|50|m|ft}} above sea level,<ref name=CAA/> with the highest point in the area reaching {{convert|60|m|ft}}.<ref name=CAA/>\n\nGiffnock experiences a [[temperate]] [[Oceanic climate|maritime climate]], like much of the [[British Isles]], with relatively cool summers and mild winters. Regular but generally light precipitation occurs throughout the year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paisley 1981\u20132010 averages|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19812010/sites/paisley.html|work=1981\u20132010 averages|publisher=Met Office|accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nGiffnock's [[built environment]] is characterised by its mixture of nineteenth and twentieth century single and two story dwellings, most of which are semi-detached or terraced. Towards the south of Giffnock the properties are generally grander two story detached villas, commonly built with local sandstone<ref name=CAA/> many of which are now [[List of listed buildings in Eastwood, East Renfrewshire|listed buildings]].\nGiffnock is a [[Postcodes in the United Kingdom|postal district]] within the [[post town]] of Glasgow in the [[G postcode area]]. Giffnock consists of postcode district G46, which also extends beyond the town boundary to include neighbouring settlements [[Kennishead]], [[Thornliebank]], [[Deaconsbank]], [[Carnwadric]] and [[Arden, Glasgow|Arden]].\n\n==Demography==\n{{see also|Demography of Scotland}}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em; font-size: 90%; text-align:center;\"\n|+'''Giffnock compared according to [[United Kingdom Census 2001|UK Census 2001]]'''<ref name=\"Population\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Population&mainLevel=CouncilArea&mainArea=East+Renfrewshire&mainText=&mainTextExplicitMatch=null&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |title=Comparative Population Profile: East Renfrewshire Council Area, Scotland |publisher=scrol.gov.uk |year=2001 |accessdate=19 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305120417/http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Population&mainLevel=CouncilArea&mainArea=East+Renfrewshire&mainText=&mainTextExplicitMatch=null&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |archivedate=5 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|-\n!\n!style=\"padding:2px;\"|Giffnock\n!style=\"padding:2px;\"|East Renfrewshire\n!style=\"padding:2px;\"|Scotland\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Total population\n|16,178||89,311||5,062,011\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[British nationality law|Foreign born]]\n|5.4%||3.8%||3.8%\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Over 75 years old\n|9.3%||6.9%||7.1%\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Unemployed\n|2%||2.5%||3.9%\n|}\n\nAccording to the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]], the [[List of census localities in Scotland|census locality]] (town and sub-area) of Giffnock had a total resident population of 16,178, or 18% of the total of East Renfrewshire.<ref name=\"Population\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Population&mainLevel=Locality&mainText=Giffnock&mainTextExplicitMatch=false&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |title=Comparative Population Profile: Giffnock Locality, Scotland |publisher=scrol.gov.uk |year=2001 |accessdate=19 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030405115504/http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=population |archivedate=5 April 2003 |df=dmy }}</ref> The [[median]] age of males and females living in Giffnock was 39 and 43 respectively, compared to 37 and 39 years for those in the whole of Scotland.<ref name=\"Population\"/> Fifty six percent were married, 3.5% were [[Cohabitation|cohabiting]] couples, 6.9% were lone parent families and 28.7% of households were made up of individuals.<ref name=\"Population\"/><ref name=\"Household\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Household&mainLevel=Locality&mainText=Giffnock&mainTextExplicitMatch=false&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130423205740/http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Household&mainLevel=Locality&mainText=Giffnock&mainTextExplicitMatch=false&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 April 2013 |title=Comparative Household Profile: Giffnock Locality, Scotland |publisher=scrol.gov.uk |year=2001 |accessdate=19 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe place of birth of the towns residents was 94.4% United Kingdom (including 87.8% from Scotland), 0.6% [[Republic of Ireland]], 0.9% from other [[European Union]] countries and 4.2% from elsewhere in the world.<ref name=\"Population\"/> Compared with the average [[demography of Scotland]], Giffnock has higher proportions of people born outside the Europe and people over [[Pensions in the United Kingdom|pensionable age]].<ref name=\"Population\"/>\n\nOf residents 16\u201374, 39.6% were in full-time employment, 12.1% in part-time employment, 8.9% self-employed and 2% unemployed compared with Scotland as a whole which has 40.3%, 11.1%, 6.6% and 4% respectively. Additionally, in Giffnock 4.2% students have jobs while 5.2% do not, 16% are retired, 5.7% look after their home or family, 3.9% are permanently sick or disabled, and 2.4% are economically inactive for other reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Employment&mainLevel=Locality&mainText=Giffnock&mainTextExplicitMatch=false&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130423202916/http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Employment&mainLevel=Locality&mainText=Giffnock&mainTextExplicitMatch=false&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 April 2013 |title=Comparative Employment Profile: Giffnock Locality, Scotland |publisher=scrol.gov.uk |year=2001 |accessdate=19 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[Image:Giffnock-Railway-Station.jpg|thumb|right|[[Giffnock railway station]]|alt=Giffnock railway station]]\nThe area has a number of high-volume road links to neighbouring Glasgow. The [[A77 road|A77]] main Glasgow to [[Kilmarnock]] road passes through the centre of the town and crosses the [[A727 road|A727]] from [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] to [[East Kilbride]] at the Eastwood Toll. The nearest motorway is the [[M77 motorway|M77]], of which Junction 3 [[Darnley]] is the [[Interchange (road)|interchange]] for Giffnock.\n\nGiffnock lies within the [[Strathclyde Partnership for Transport]] [[Passenger transport executive]] and is served by three railway stations, all of which are managed by [[Abellio ScotRail]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/GFN.html|publisher=nationalrail.co.uk|author=[[National Rail]]|date=23 January 2007|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Station Facilities: Giffnock (GFN)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/WCR.html|publisher=nationalrail.co.uk|author=[[National Rail]]|date=23 January 2007|accessdate=14 December 2007|title=Station Facilities: Whitecraigs (WCR)}}</ref> \n*[[Giffnock railway station]], opened on 1 January 1866,<ref name=\"butt102\">Butt (1995), page 102</ref> lies on the East Kilbride branch of the [[Glasgow South Western Line]], which runs from [[Glasgow Central railway station|Glasgow Central]] {{convert|4|mi|km|1}} north-northeast.\n*[[Whitecraigs railway station]], opened on 1 May 1903,<ref name=\"butt248\">Butt (1995), page 248</ref> lies on the Neilston branch of the [[Cathcart Circle Lines|Cathcart Circle]] {{convert|5.2|mi|km|1}} south-southwest of Glasgow Central.\n*[[Williamwood railway station]], opened on 1 May 1903,<ref name=\"butt248\">Butt (1995), page 248</ref> lies on the Neilston branch of the [[Cathcart Circle Lines|Cathcart Circle]] {{convert|5.2|mi|km|1}} south-southwest of Glasgow Central.\n\nThe closest airport is [[Glasgow Airport]], {{convert|6.8|mi|km|1}} north-west of Giffnock. This is followed by [[Glasgow Prestwick Airport]] and then [[Edinburgh Airport]].\n\nGiffnock is serviced by a number of bus routes by various operators. The main bus link to the city is the number 38 line operated by [[First Glasgow]], which runs at least every 10 minutes throughout the day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Timetables for Service Number: 38/38A|url=http://www.firstgroup.com/ukbus/glasgow/journey_planning/timetables/timetable.php?day=1&source_id=2&service=38/38A&routeid=6779791&operator=10&source=sp|work=FirstGroup timetables|publisher=Firstgroup|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{hatnote|See also: [[List of state schools in Scotland/Council Areas E-H (excluding cities)#East Renfrewshire|List of state schools in East Renfrewshire]]}}\n\nThe first evidence of education in Giffnock is of a small private school that operated in the lodge house at the Redhurst Hotel.<ref name=STS13>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=13}}</ref> Due to the increased population, the first public school opened in 1902 in the Tower Rooms of Giffnock United Free Church, known now as the Orchardhill Parish Church.<ref name=STS13/>\n\nGiffnock has a number of high schools, including [[St Ninian's High School, Giffnock|St Ninian's High School]], a [[co-educational]] Roman Catholic High School which was built in 1984 and is Scotland's top-performing state school.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/7288817.stm BBC \u2013 Spat over top school's catchment], retrieved 13 March 2008</ref> St Ninian's was the first state-funded school in Scotland to abandon the [[Standard Grade]] examination system in favour of the [[Education in Scotland|Higher Still system]], using Access 3, [[Intermediate 1]] and [[Intermediate 2]] for pupils in third and fourth year, while maintaining [[Higher (Scottish)|Highers]] in fifth year and [[Advanced Highers]] in sixth year.<ref name=Int2>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1945635.stm BBC News \u2013 School scraps Standard Grades], Retrieved 22 April 2006</ref>\nThe school roll was 1784 as of September 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/scottishschoolsonline/schools/stninianshighschooleastrenfrewshire.asp|title=St Ninian's High School - East Renfrewshire|publisher=EducationScotland.gov.uk|accessdate=3 September 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915115718/http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/scottishschoolsonline/schools/stninianshighschooleastrenfrewshire.asp|archivedate=15 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, Giffnock has a library<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=2161|title=Giffnock library \u2013 East Renfrewshire Council |publisher=[[East Renfrewshire Council]] |accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> and two primary schools: Giffnock Primary School and Braidbar Primary school, non-denominational feeder primary schools for [[Woodfarm High School]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About our schools|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1740|work=East Renfrewshire Council official website|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Culture and community==\n\n===Religion===\n[[Image:TBGiffMap1923.jpg|thumb|300px|Map of Giffnock in early 1900s|alt=Map of Giffnock in early 1900s]]\n\nUntil the end of the nineteenth century, Giffnock had no church buildings, and religious meetings took place in the waiting room of Giffnock Railway Station and, later, in the clubhouse at Eastwood Golf Course.<ref name=CAA/> Orchardhill Parish Church, designed by HE Clifford and completed in 1899, was the first church built within Giffnock.<ref name=CAA/> Now a [[Listed building|category B listed building]],<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB5123|desc=Orchardhill Church of Scotland, Church Road, Giffnock|cat=B|access-date=28 March 2019}}</ref> the Church is built in a [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic revival]] style of architecture and is built mainly of locally quarried stone.<ref name=CAA/>\nAlso located in Giffnock is [[Giffnock Synagogue]], founded in 1938 and home to the largest Jewish religious congregation in Scotland.<ref name=Synagogue>{{cite web |title=Synagogue membership in the UK |url=http://www.jpr.org.uk/downloads/Synagogue%20membership.pdf |work=Synagogue membership in the UK |publisher=Institute for Jewish Policy Research |accessdate=20 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60Mnkiz1A?url=http://www.jpr.org.uk/downloads/Synagogue%20membership.pdf |archivedate=22 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Recreation===\nIn 1936 the Tudor Cinema was constructed in Giffnock by Alex Frutin. It opened in December as a \"superb suburban cinema\". The Tudor was an [[Art Deco]] style building and is considered Glasgow's first \"entertainment complex\", featuring a ballroom and restaurant as well as the 2,400-seat cinema.<ref name=STS15>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=15}}</ref>\n\nGiffnock has numerous parks, including [[Rouken Glen]], Huntly Park and Eastwood Park,<ref>[https://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurefirst11438.html Eastwood House] at [[Gazetteer for Scotland]]</ref> where the [[East Renfrewshire Council]] offices are based.<ref>[https://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurefirst11437.html Eastwood Park] at [[Gazetteer for Scotland]]</ref> There remains some ancient woodland in Giffnock, which could be as old as 8,000 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Broadleaved & Mixed Woodland [PDF]|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=951|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:PanoramaGiffnock.jpg|thumb|300px|Panaoramic View of ''Fenwick Road'', the main street in Giffnock.|alt=Panaoramic View of ''Fenwick Road'', the main street in Giffnock]]\nThe lands of Rouken Glen Park originally belonged to the [[The Crown|Scottish Crown]]. Ownership shifted to the [[Earl of Eglinton]] when [[James V of Scotland|James V]] presented the land to [[Hugh Montgomerie, 1st Earl of Eglinton]] on the marriage of his son in 1530.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://personal.cis.strath.ac.uk/~davidm/website/history01.htm |title=History of Rouken Glen |publisher=Personal.cis.strath.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref> The area of the estate was farmed until the end of the 18th century and, in 1858, the estate was purchased by local merchant Walter Crum. Alexander Crum inherited the estate in 1879 and is responsible for the layout of Rouken Glen as it is today. On his sudden death in August 1893, the house passed into the hands of his brother, William Graham Crum, who later sold the estate to Archibald Cameron Corbett, MP (later [[Archibald Corbett, 1st Baron Rowallan|Lord Rowallan]]) on 19 May 1905.<ref name=STS22>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=22}}</ref> In 1906 the estate was given to the City of Glasgow by Lord Rowallan, with the provision that it be for the \"citizens of Glasgow for all time\".<ref name=STS22/> Rouken Glen Park was officially opened on Saturday, 25 May 1906 by Lord Rowallan.<ref name=STS22/>\n\nEastwood Park Leisure Centre has a 25-metre (82&nbsp;ft) swimming pool, two additional smaller pools and two gyms. Activities in the [[leisure centre]] include casual swimming, swimming lessons, pool fun sessions, fitness classes, a sauna and gym sessions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eastwood Park Leisure|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=2203|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>  \n[[Greenbank Garden]], an 18th-century house and garden owned by the [[National Trust for Scotland]], is located between Clarkston and Newton Mearns, near Giffnock. The house has a {{convert|2.5|acre}} [[walled garden]], sixteen rooms and barns and stables. This building is protected as a Category A [[listed building]].<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB18537|desc=Greenbank House, High Flenders Road, by Whitecraigs|cat=A|access-date=28 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n\nThe Giffnock North Social Club, located on Braidbar Road, is a community non-profit making venue run by its members.<ref>[http://www.giffnocknorthsocialclub.co.uk Giffnock North Social Club]</ref> The club host a wide and diverse range of live music events. Faciliies at the club include a lounge and a games room with pool tables, darts and large screen TV. It also has a function hall which can be hired out for special occasions, accommodating up to 150 guests.\n\n=== Sport ===\nIn 1905 the Whitecraigs Golf Club was founded.<ref name=Golf>{{cite web|title=Whitecraigs Golf Club |url=http://www.scotlands-golf-courses.com/index.php?option=com_mtree&task=viewlink&link_id=654 |work=Scotlands Golf Courses |publisher=scotlands-golf-courses.com |accessdate=12 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113161336/http://www.scotlands-golf-courses.com/index.php?option=com_mtree&task=viewlink&link_id=654 |archivedate=13 November 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> The course was originally designed by [[Willie Fernie (golfer)|Willie Fernie]], who was [[The Open Championship]] winner in 1883 and also designed the [[Turnberry (golf course)|Ailsa course at Turnberry]].<ref name=Golf/> Alterations to the course were made in the 1930s by [[James Braid (golfer)|James Braid]], who won [[The Open Championship]] five times between 1901 and 1910.<ref name=Golf/>\n\nMany golfing events have been hosted by the Whitecraigs Golf Club. The club was visited by the United States [[Ryder Cup]] teams of 1929 and 1933. The teams included many golfing legends such as [[Walter Hagen]], [[Gene Sarazen]] and [[Horton Smith]]. Whitecraigs hosted the [[World Senior Championship]] in 1976 and 1978. In 1983, [[Jack Nicklaus]] visited the club to play an exhibition match and run a clinic.\n\n[[Whitecraigs RFC|Whitecraigs Rugby Club]] is a rugby union team based at Newton Mearns, near Giffnock. As of the 2011\u20132012 season, the team competes in the [[Scottish Premiership Division One|Scottish Premiership Division A]].<ref>{{cite web|title=RBS Championship - RBS Championship A |url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/whitecraigs/s/division-6826.html?d_id=5361&page=table |publisher=Whitecraigs Rugby Club |accessdate=15 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233655/http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/whitecraigs/s/division-6826.html?d_id=5361&page=table |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n== Public services ==\nGiffnock forms part of the Western water and sewerage regions of Scotland. [[Waste management]] is provided by the East Renfrewshire local council. Water supplies are provided by [[Scottish Water]], a [[government-owned corporation]] of the [[Scottish Government]]. Giffnock's [[Distribution Network Operator]] for electricity is [[Scottish Power]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.energylinx.co.uk/distribution_network_operators.htm|publisher=energylinx.co.uk|year=2007|accessdate=31 March 2013|title=Electricity Distribution Network Operators|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114055937/http://www.energylinx.co.uk/distribution_network_operators.htm|archivedate=14 January 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[NHS board]] is [[NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde]]. [[Strathclyde Fire and Rescue]] is the [[statutory]] [[Fire services in Scotland|fire and rescue service]]. The nearest fire station is in the neighbouring settlement of [[Clarkston, East Renfrewshire|Clarkston]]<ref>{{cite web |title=East Ayrshire and East Renfrewshire |url=http://www.strathclydefire.org/your-area/e-ayrshire--e-renfrewshire.aspx |publisher=Strathclyde Fire & Rescue |accessdate=31 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921060252/http://www.strathclydefire.org/your-area/e-ayrshire--e-renfrewshire.aspx |archivedate=21 September 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nPolicing in Giffnock is provided by Police Scotland. The [[Strathclyde Partnership for Transport]], a [[Scottish public bodies|public body in Scotland]], has direct operational responsibilities, such as supporting (and in some cases running) local bus services and managing [[integrated ticketing]] in Giffnock and other areas from the former [[Strathclyde]] region.<ref name=\"SPT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spt.co.uk/about/index.html|author=[[Strathclyde Partnership for Transport]]|publisher=spt.co.uk|date=5 September 2007|accessdate=11 February 2008|title=Who we are|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080408063150/http://www.spt.co.uk/about/index.html |archivedate = 8 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Transport Scotland]] manages the local rail network.<ref name=\"SPT\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Gordon Brown]], [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] from 2007\u20132010\n* [[Daniel McGillivray Brown]], chemist \n* [[Aiden McGeady]], Ireland international footballer\n* [[Andrew Robertson]], Scotland international footballer\n* [[Calum Gallagher]], footballer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{Butt-Stations}}\n* Eastwood District Libraries. (1988). ''Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.'' {{ISBN|1-871215-00-5}}.\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.scotcities.com/cathcart/eastwood.htm Giffnock & Netherlee illustrated guide] at ''Scotcities''\n\n{{East Renfrewshire}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Giffnock| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in East Renfrewshire]]\n[[Category:Greater Glasgow]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Townin East Renfrewshire, Scotland}}\n{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|static_image_name = Giffnock, East Renfrewshire. - geograph.org.uk - 429703.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Shops on Fenwick Road\n|country              = Scotland\n|official_name        = Giffnock\n|gaelic_name          = Giofnag<ref name=GaelicName/>\n|scots_name           = Giffnock<ref name=RailwayNames>{{cite web|title=List of Railway station names |url=http://newsnetscotland.com/index.php/component/content/article/2999-list-of-railway-station-names.html |accessdate=20 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130122064223/http://newsnetscotland.com/index.php/component/content/article/2999-list-of-railway-station-names.html |archivedate=22 January 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> \n|population= 16,178\n|population_ref= ([[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 Census]])\n|os_grid_reference    = NS565585\n|coordinates          = {{coord|55.805109|-4.294610 |display=inline,title}}\n|map_type             = Scotland\n| pushpin_map             = Scotland East Renfrewshire#Scotland Glasgow\n|lieutenancy_scotland = [[Renfrewshire (historic)|Renfrewshire]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[East Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Renfrewshire]]\n|constituency_scottish_parliament = [[Eastwood (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Eastwood]]\n|post_town            = GLASGOW\n|postcode_district    = G46\n|postcode_area        = G\n|dial_code            = 0141\n|edinburgh_distance= {{convert|51|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[Boxing the compass|ENE]]\n|london_distance= {{convert|344|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[Boxing the compass|SSE]]\n }}\n'''Giffnock ''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u026a|f|n|\u0259|k}}; {{lang-sco|Giffnock}}; {{lang-gd|Giofnag}}, {{IPA-gd|\u02c8k\u02b2ifnak|pron}}) is an affluent suburban town and the administrative centre of [[East Renfrewshire]] in the [[Central Lowlands]] of [[Scotland]]. It lies {{convert|3.7|mi|km|1}} east of [[Barrhead]], {{convert|5.6|mi|km|1}} east-southeast of [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] and {{convert|5.3|mi|km|1}} northwest of [[East Kilbride]], at the southwest of the [[Greater Glasgow|Greater Glasgow conurbation]]. Giffnock is mentioned in documents as early as the seventeenth century as a scattered agricultural settlement. In the late eighteenth century, [[Archibald Montgomerie, 11th Earl of Eglinton|Archibald Montgomerie]], the [[Earl of Eglinton]], was forced to partition the land into a number of smaller properties.\n\nThe urbanisation and development of Giffnock began in the mid to late nineteenth century with the construction of several sandstone [[Quarry|quarries]], and this prompted the development of the first railway link with nearby Glasgow. Large-scale quarrying continued in Giffnock for almost a century. However, the quarrying ceased by the 1920s, and other uses were found for the quarries. An additional railway service began at the start of the twentieth century, closely followed by the arrival of [[Glasgow Corporation Tramways]]. Giffnock's relative closeness to Glasgow coupled with the local industry and good transports links helped it to develop into a suburban town, as many wealthy merchants chose to construct villas in its smog-free environs and commute daily to the city. \n \nAlthough heavy industry died out in the area during the early twentieth century, as part of Scotland's densely populated [[Central Belt]], Giffnock has continued to grow as a [[Commuter town|dormitory town]], supported by its position within the Greater Glasgow area, from roughly 1,425 residents in the early twentieth century to 16,178 in 2001. Expansion continues due to several new housing developments; however, much of the land is now urbanised or designated [[park]]land, leaving little room for further expansion.\n\n==History==\nThe [[Scottish Gaelic language|Scottish Gaelic]] name for Giffnock is Giofnag<ref name=GaelicName>{{cite web|title=Giffnock|url=http://www.gaelicplacenames.org/databasedetails.php?id=383|work=Gaelic Place-names of Scotland|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> and is of partially [[Common Brittonic|Brythonic]] and [[Scottish Gaelic|Gaelic]] origin. 'Cefn' (i.e. 'Giff') comes from the Brythonic meaning 'ridge' and the Gaelic ''cnoc'' (i.e. 'nock') meaning \"hill\". In Gaelic, ''oc'' or ''og'' is a [[diminutive]], and thus when added to ''cefn'' gives Giffnock the meaning of \"Little Ridge\".<ref name=STS2/>\n\nThe first written mention of Giffnock came in 1530, when [[James V of Scotland|James V]] presented Rockend (Ruken) Mill and the surrounding lands to [[Hugh Montgomerie, 1st Earl of Eglinton]].<ref name=CAA/>\nThe settlement of Giffnock first appeared as Gisnock, in an atlas created by [[Dutch people|Dutch]] [[cartographer]] [[Joan Blaeu]] in 1654, the first atlas of Scotland.<ref name=STS2>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=2}}</ref> Giffnock was primarily a scattered farming community until the late 1780s, when [[Archibald Montgomerie, 11th Earl of Eglinton]] was forced to partition the land into a number of small properties for sale to raise finances.<ref name=BBCGiffnock>{{cite web|title=BBC Scotland \u2013 Giffnock (East Renfrewshire)|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/landscapes/giffnock/|work=landscapes|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Industry===\nIn 1835, the first [[sandstone]] [[quarry]] in Giffnock opened. Before long, the town became known for this industry, and at its peak, there were four quarries in Giffnock, three surface quarries and one underground quarry, which together employed over 1,000 men.<ref name=CAA/><ref name=Quarries>{{cite web|title=Quarries \u2013 Portal to the Past|url=http://www.portaltothepast.co.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3210|work=Portal to the Past|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> The quarries produced two types of sandstone: \"liver rock\" and \"moor rock\". \"Liver rock\" was particularly popular with masons thanks to its lack of [[Stratum|stratification]], which made the stone easy to work with. In 1854, a coal mining firm managed by civil engineers [[Hugh Baird (engineer)|Hugh Baird]] and [[Robert Stevenson (civil engineer)|Robert Stevenson]] took over the running of the quarries and by 1866 the [[Glasgow South Western Line|Busby Railway]] was built, allowing them to transport the stone by rail.<ref name=Quarries/><ref>{{cite web|title=Busby Railway|url=http://www.railbrit.co.uk/Busby_Railway/frame.htm|work=RailBrit|publisher=RailBrit|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref>  Originally, a lower level line was laid from [[Giffnock railway station]] into the Orchard Quarry to facilitate the extraction of the stone.<ref name=STS5>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=5}}</ref>\n\nSandstone from the Giffnock quarries was primarily used within the nearby city of [[Glasgow]] and can be found in older parts of the [[University of Glasgow]] and the interior of [[Kelvingrove Art Gallery]].<ref name=Quarries/> A small amount of trade was done with Belfast, and some of the finer \"liver rock\" was even transported as far as America and South Africa to build both buildings and monuments.<ref name=STS5/>\n\nQuarrying in Giffnock continued until 1912 when, due to flooding and the high cost of extracting stone, work ceased. Numerous ventures tried to revitalise the quarries for other purposes, including the cultivation of [[mushroom]]s in the tunnels. As the pits began to fill with water, it became an issue that needed to be resolved. In the early 1930s, [[William Beardmore and Company|William Bearmore & Co]] began tipping [[slag]] from the production of steel into the Giffnock quarries.<ref name=STS6>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=6}}</ref> The slag tipping continued until 1969, when Derek Crouch Limited began scrap metal extraction, which lasted until the late 1970s. Today the ground is a wasteland.<ref name=STS7>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=7}}</ref>\n\nCoal mining was also carried out in Giffnock, between 1850 and 1926. The coal produced was of a very poor quality and was of little value to householders. The main use of Giffnock coal was with commercial and industrial customers such as Busby [[History of manufactured gas|Gas Works]].<ref name=STS8>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=8}}</ref>\n\n===Urbanisation and expansion===\nThe opening of [[Giffnock railway station]] in 1866 allowed business people to build sandstone villas and commute daily to the city. At the time, it was much more desirable to live in Giffnock than to live in the smog-polluted city.<ref name=\"STS10\">{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=10}}</ref> By the early 1890s, residential Giffnock began to grow around the railway station and Eastwood Toll,<ref name=Timeline>{{cite web|title=Timeline \u2013 Giffnock|url=http://www.portaltothepast.co.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3290|work=Portal to the past|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> and by 1892 gas was introduced to the area.<ref name=Timeline/> [[Gas lighting|Gas street lamps]] were erected by Busby and District Gas Company in 1893; however, these were supported by a voluntary subscription that many households refused to pay, leaving many areas unlit. It was not until October 1896, when Eastwood Parish Council took over street lighting, that the area was consistently lit at night.<ref name=\"STS13\"/>\n\nIn 1903, a second railway station was opened in Giffnock, [[Whitecraigs railway station]].<ref name=\"butt248\"/> The station lay on the [[Lanarkshire and Ayrshire Railway]], originally built to provide a through route from the [[Lanarkshire]] coalfields to ports such as [[Ardrossan]] on the [[Ayrshire]] coast.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lanarkshire and Ayrshire Railway|url=http://www.railbrit.co.uk/Lanarkshire_and_Ayrshire_Railway/frame.htm|publisher=RailBrit|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe growth of Giffnock was furthered in 1905 by the arrival of the first [[Glasgow Corporation Tramways]] tram in the town.<ref name=Timeline/> The addition of this tram link and the nearby Whitecraigs railway station helped the popularity of Giffnock as a weekend destination and lead to the opening of [[Rouken Glen]] park in 1906 by Archibald Corbett (later Lord Rowallan), the M.P. for Tradeston.<ref name=Timeline/> The Giffnock tramline was one of Glasgow Corporation Tramways's most profitable routes; up to 15,000 travelled to Giffnock on a Sunday to visit Rouken Glen.<ref name=\"STS13\"/>\n\nDuring the great housing boom of the late 1930s, Giffnock began to grow rapidly. Between 1930 and 1940, as many as 3,000 dwellings were constructed, and the population rose dramatically, from 1,425 to 3,471 in 1939 and 9,144 in 1951.<ref name=STS15/>\n\n[[File:Rudolf Hess - Bf 110D Werk Nr 3869 - Wreckage - Bonnyton Moor.jpg|thumb|left|alt=The wreckage of [[Rudolf Hess|Hess's]] [[Messerschmitt Bf 110|Bf 110]]\n crashed in a busby field]]\nOn 7 May 1941, during the [[Greenock Blitz]] of [[World War II]], the [[Nazi German]] [[Luftwaffe]] dropped a group of bombs over Giffnock, but only two houses were destroyed.<ref name=CAA/> \nOn 10 May 1941, [[Rudolf Hess]], a prominent Nazi politician and [[Deputy F\u00fchrer|deputy]] to [[Adolf Hitler]] parachuted out of his [[Messerschmitt Bf 110D]] near [[Waterfoot, East Renfrewshire|Waterfoot]].<ref name=McRoberts>{{cite book | last = McRoberts | first = Douglas | title = Lions Rampant: The Story of 602 Spitfire Squadron | publisher = William Kimber | series =  | edition = | year = 1985 | page = 143 | url = | id = | isbn = 0-7183-0572-8 | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> Hess had flown solo to Scotland in an attempt to negotiate peace with the United Kingdom. He was detained by the [[Home Guard (United Kingdom)|Home Guard]] in the battalion headquarters in the Giffnock Scout hall, where he was questioned by Major Donald, the Assistant Group Officer of the [[Royal Observer Corps|Glasgow Royal Observer Corps]] before being transferred to [[Maryhill Barracks]] in Glasgow the following day. The wreckage of Hess's aircraft was salvaged by 63 Maintenance Unit (MU) between 11 and 16 May 1941.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yourarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk/index.php?title=Hess,_Rudolf_%281894-1987%29_German_Politician |title=National Archives (UK), A2A, AIR 29/1019 |publisher=Yourarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=7 August 2013 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Part of the aeroplane is now in London's [[Imperial War Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airmuseumsuk.org/museum/IWMLondon/index.htm |title=Imperial War Museum London: Aircraft Collection|website= airmuseumsuk.org|accessdate= 10 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nProposals were put forward in 2008 to expand the town with the building of 178 houses on Braidbar Quarries next to Huntly Park, involving the Park closing for a period of two years. However, following 2,000 objections from local people and the opposition of the Scottish Government's reporter, East Renfrewshire Council abandoned the plans in October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Braidbar quarry housing and remediation plans announcement|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3048|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Governance==\n{{see also|History of local government in Scotland}}\nGiffnock is represented by several tiers of elected government. Giffnock Community Council forms the lowest tier of governance whose statutory role is to communicate local opinion to local and central government.<ref name=\"Giffnock Council\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1871|title=Community Councils|date=|accessdate=19 December 2012|author=East Renfrewshire Council|publisher=eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk}}</ref> It is one of ten [[List of community council areas in Scotland|community councils]] of the [[East Renfrewshire]] [[council area]].<ref name=\"Giffnock Council\"/>\n\nEast Renfrewshire Council, the unitary [[Local government in Scotland|local council]], is based in Giffnock and is the Executive, [[Deliberation|deliberative]] and [[legislative]] body responsible for [[Local government in Scotland|local governance]]. The [[Scottish Parliament]] is responsible for [[Devolution|devolved matters]] such as [[Education in Scotland|education]], [[Health in Scotland|health]] and [[Scots law|justice]],<ref name=\"devolved matters\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotlandoffice.gov.uk/what-we-do/reserved-and-devolved-matters.html |title=Reserved and devolved matters |publisher=Scotland Office |accessdate=19 December 2012|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061004074305/http://www.scotlandoffice.gov.uk/what-we-do/reserved-and-devolved-matters.html |archivedate = 4 October 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> while [[reserved and excepted matters|reserved matters]] are dealt with by the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]].\n\nGiffnock forms part of the [[United Kingdom constituencies|county constituency]] of [[East Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Renfrewshire]], electing one member of parliament (MP) to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] of the Parliament of the United Kingdom. [[Kirsten Oswald]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/kirsten-oswald/4413 |publisher=United Kingdom Parliament|title=Kirsten Oswald MP|accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref> of the [[Scottish National Party|SNP]] was elected as MP for East Renfrewshire in the [[List of MPs for constituencies in Scotland 2015\u201317|2015 General Election]]. Before the constituency's creation in 2005, Giffnock lay in the [[Eastwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Eastwood Constituency]]. For the purposes of the [[Scottish Parliament]], Giffnock forms part of the [[Eastwood (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Eastwood Constituency]], which is represented by [[Jackson Carlaw]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]], of the [[Scottish Conservative Party]].\n\n==Geography==\n{{Geographic Location\n|title = '''Neighbouring towns, villages and places.'''\n|Northwest = [[Thornliebank]]\n|North = [[Shawlands]]\n|Northeast = [[Muirend]]\n|West = [[Darnley]]\n|Centre = Giffnock\n|East = [[Castlemilk]]\n|Southwest = [[Newton Mearns]]\n|South = [[Waterfoot, East Renfrewshire|Waterfoot]]\n|Southeast = [[Clarkston, East Renfrewshire|Clarkston]]\n}}\n\n{{climate chart\n| [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]]\n|1.8|6.9|148.2\n|1.8|7.4|104.9\n|3.0|9.6|112.3\n|4.8|12.6|63.6\n|7.3|15.9|67.5\n|10.1|18.1|66.4\n|12.0|19.7|73.0\n|11.7|19.2|92.5\n|9.7|16.4|112.5\n|6.7|12.7|143.1\n|4.0|9.4|126.4\n|1.7|6.9|135.2\n|float=right\n|clear=both\n|source=[http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19812010/sites/paisley.html Met Office]\n}}\n\nAt {{coord|55|48|9|N|4|17|43|W|type:city}} (55.803\u00b0, \u22124.30\u00b0) Giffnock is situated in Scotland's [[Central Lowlands]]. The town lies {{convert|3.7|mi|km|1}} east of [[Barrhead]], {{convert|5.3|mi|km|1}} northwest of [[East Kilbride]] and {{convert|4.3|mi|km|1}} south-southwest of Glasgow. \nThe territory of Giffnock is contiguous with Glasgow and forms part of [[Greater Glasgow]], the [[List of conurbations in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom's fifth largest conurbation]].\n\nGiffnock is situated on the [[plateau]] that encircles Glasgow. It is at edge of the area that defines the basin that Glasgow has developed within.<ref name=CAA>{{cite web|last=Cahill|first=Andrew J|title=Conservation Area Appraisal \u2013 Giffnock|format=PDF|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=8424&p=0|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> \nThe underlay is composed mainly of sedimentary rocks and [[Freestone (masonry)|freestone]] from the Strathclyde and Clackmannan groups of early to mid [[Carboniferous]] age (354 to 316 million years).<ref name=CAA/> \nThe relatively soft and easily eroded rocks have resulted in the landform in the area being mostly flat with gentle undulations.<ref name=CAA/>\nThe area of Giffnock is typically around {{convert|45|m|ft}} to {{convert|50|m|ft}} above sea level,<ref name=CAA/> with the highest point in the area reaching {{convert|60|m|ft}}.<ref name=CAA/>\n\nGiffnock experiences a [[temperate]] [[Oceanic climate|maritime climate]], like much of the [[British Isles]], with relatively cool summers and mild winters. Regular but generally light precipitation occurs throughout the year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paisley 1981\u20132010 averages|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19812010/sites/paisley.html|work=1981\u20132010 averages|publisher=Met Office|accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nGiffnock's [[built environment]] is characterised by its mixture of nineteenth and twentieth century single and two story dwellings, most of which are semi-detached or terraced. Towards the south of Giffnock the properties are generally grander two story detached villas, commonly built with local sandstone<ref name=CAA/> many of which are now [[List of listed buildings in Eastwood, East Renfrewshire|listed buildings]].\nGiffnock is a [[Postcodes in the United Kingdom|postal district]] within the [[post town]] of Glasgow in the [[G postcode area]]. Giffnock consists of postcode district G46, which also extends beyond the town boundary to include neighbouring settlements [[Kennishead]], [[Thornliebank]], [[Deaconsbank]], [[Carnwadric]] and [[Arden, Glasgow|Arden]].\n\n==Demography==\n{{see also|Demography of Scotland}}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em; font-size: 90%; text-align:center;\"\n|+'''Giffnock compared according to [[United Kingdom Census 2001|UK Census 2001]]'''<ref name=\"Population\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Population&mainLevel=CouncilArea&mainArea=East+Renfrewshire&mainText=&mainTextExplicitMatch=null&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |title=Comparative Population Profile: East Renfrewshire Council Area, Scotland |publisher=scrol.gov.uk |year=2001 |accessdate=19 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305120417/http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Population&mainLevel=CouncilArea&mainArea=East+Renfrewshire&mainText=&mainTextExplicitMatch=null&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |archivedate=5 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|-\n!\n!style=\"padding:2px;\"|Giffnock\n!style=\"padding:2px;\"|East Renfrewshire\n!style=\"padding:2px;\"|Scotland\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Total population\n|16,178||89,311||5,062,011\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[British nationality law|Foreign born]]\n|5.4%||3.8%||3.8%\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Over 75 years old\n|9.3%||6.9%||7.1%\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Unemployed\n|2%||2.5%||3.9%\n|}\n\nAccording to the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]], the [[List of census localities in Scotland|census locality]] (town and sub-area) of Giffnock had a total resident population of 16,178, or 18% of the total of East Renfrewshire.<ref name=\"Population\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Population&mainLevel=Locality&mainText=Giffnock&mainTextExplicitMatch=false&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |title=Comparative Population Profile: Giffnock Locality, Scotland |publisher=scrol.gov.uk |year=2001 |accessdate=19 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030405115504/http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=population |archivedate=5 April 2003 |df=dmy }}</ref> The [[median]] age of males and females living in Giffnock was 39 and 43 respectively, compared to 37 and 39 years for those in the whole of Scotland.<ref name=\"Population\"/> Fifty six percent were married, 3.5% were [[Cohabitation|cohabiting]] couples, 6.9% were lone parent families and 28.7% of households were made up of individuals.<ref name=\"Population\"/><ref name=\"Household\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Household&mainLevel=Locality&mainText=Giffnock&mainTextExplicitMatch=false&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130423205740/http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Household&mainLevel=Locality&mainText=Giffnock&mainTextExplicitMatch=false&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 April 2013 |title=Comparative Household Profile: Giffnock Locality, Scotland |publisher=scrol.gov.uk |year=2001 |accessdate=19 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe place of birth of the towns residents was 94.4% United Kingdom (including 87.8% from Scotland), 0.6% [[Republic of Ireland]], 0.9% from other [[European Union]] countries and 4.2% from elsewhere in the world.<ref name=\"Population\"/> Compared with the average [[demography of Scotland]], Giffnock has higher proportions of people born outside the Europe and people over [[Pensions in the United Kingdom|pensionable age]].<ref name=\"Population\"/>\n\nOf residents 16\u201374, 39.6% were in full-time employment, 12.1% in part-time employment, 8.9% self-employed and 2% unemployed compared with Scotland as a whole which has 40.3%, 11.1%, 6.6% and 4% respectively. Additionally, in Giffnock 4.2% students have jobs while 5.2% do not, 16% are retired, 5.7% look after their home or family, 3.9% are permanently sick or disabled, and 2.4% are economically inactive for other reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Employment&mainLevel=Locality&mainText=Giffnock&mainTextExplicitMatch=false&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130423202916/http://www.scrol.gov.uk/scrol/browser/profile.jsp?profile=Employment&mainLevel=Locality&mainText=Giffnock&mainTextExplicitMatch=false&compLevel=CountryProfile&compText=&compTextExplicitMatch=null |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 April 2013 |title=Comparative Employment Profile: Giffnock Locality, Scotland |publisher=scrol.gov.uk |year=2001 |accessdate=19 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[Image:Giffnock-Railway-Station.jpg|thumb|right|[[Giffnock railway station]]|alt=Giffnock railway station]]\nThe area has a number of high-volume road links to neighbouring Glasgow. The [[A77 road|A77]] main Glasgow to [[Kilmarnock]] road passes through the centre of the town and crosses the [[A727 road|A727]] from [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] to [[East Kilbride]] at the Eastwood Toll. The nearest motorway is the [[M77 motorway|M77]], of which Junction 3 [[Darnley]] is the [[Interchange (road)|interchange]] for Giffnock.\n\nGiffnock lies within the [[Strathclyde Partnership for Transport]] [[Passenger transport executive]] and is served by three railway stations, all of which are managed by [[Abellio ScotRail]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/GFN.html|publisher=nationalrail.co.uk|author=[[National Rail]]|date=23 January 2007|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Station Facilities: Giffnock (GFN)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/WCR.html|publisher=nationalrail.co.uk|author=[[National Rail]]|date=23 January 2007|accessdate=14 December 2007|title=Station Facilities: Whitecraigs (WCR)}}</ref> \n*[[Giffnock railway station]], opened on 1 January 1866,<ref name=\"butt102\">Butt (1995), page 102</ref> lies on the East Kilbride branch of the [[Glasgow South Western Line]], which runs from [[Glasgow Central railway station|Glasgow Central]] {{convert|4|mi|km|1}} north-northeast.\n*[[Whitecraigs railway station]], opened on 1 May 1903,<ref name=\"butt248\">Butt (1995), page 248</ref> lies on the Neilston branch of the [[Cathcart Circle Lines|Cathcart Circle]] {{convert|5.2|mi|km|1}} south-southwest of Glasgow Central.\n*[[Williamwood railway station]], opened on 1 May 1903,<ref name=\"butt248\">Butt (1995), page 248</ref> lies on the Neilston branch of the [[Cathcart Circle Lines|Cathcart Circle]] {{convert|5.2|mi|km|1}} south-southwest of Glasgow Central.\n\nThe closest airport is [[Glasgow Airport]], {{convert|6.8|mi|km|1}} north-west of Giffnock. This is followed by [[Glasgow Prestwick Airport]] and then [[Edinburgh Airport]].\n\nGiffnock is serviced by a number of bus routes by various operators. The main bus link to the city is the number 38 line operated by [[First Glasgow]], which runs at least every 10 minutes throughout the day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Timetables for Service Number: 38/38A|url=http://www.firstgroup.com/ukbus/glasgow/journey_planning/timetables/timetable.php?day=1&source_id=2&service=38/38A&routeid=6779791&operator=10&source=sp|work=FirstGroup timetables|publisher=Firstgroup|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{hatnote|See also: [[List of state schools in Scotland/Council Areas E-H (excluding cities)#East Renfrewshire|List of state schools in East Renfrewshire]]}}\n\nThe first evidence of education in Giffnock is of a small private school that operated in the lodge house at the Redhurst Hotel.<ref name=STS13>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=13}}</ref> Due to the increased population, the first public school opened in 1902 in the Tower Rooms of Giffnock United Free Church, known now as the Orchardhill Parish Church.<ref name=STS13/>\n\nGiffnock has a number of high schools, including [[St Ninian's High School, Giffnock|St Ninian's High School]], a [[co-educational]] Roman Catholic High School which was built in 1984 and is Scotland's top-performing state school.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/7288817.stm BBC \u2013 Spat over top school's catchment], retrieved 13 March 2008</ref> St Ninian's was the first state-funded school in Scotland to abandon the [[Standard Grade]] examination system in favour of the [[Education in Scotland|Higher Still system]], using Access 3, [[Intermediate 1]] and [[Intermediate 2]] for pupils in third and fourth year, while maintaining [[Higher (Scottish)|Highers]] in fifth year and [[Advanced Highers]] in sixth year.<ref name=Int2>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1945635.stm BBC News \u2013 School scraps Standard Grades], Retrieved 22 April 2006</ref>\nThe school roll was 1784 as of September 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/scottishschoolsonline/schools/stninianshighschooleastrenfrewshire.asp|title=St Ninian's High School - East Renfrewshire|publisher=EducationScotland.gov.uk|accessdate=3 September 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915115718/http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/scottishschoolsonline/schools/stninianshighschooleastrenfrewshire.asp|archivedate=15 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, Giffnock has a library<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=2161|title=Giffnock library \u2013 East Renfrewshire Council |publisher=[[East Renfrewshire Council]] |accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> and two primary schools: Giffnock Primary School and Braidbar Primary school, non-denominational feeder primary schools for [[Woodfarm High School]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About our schools|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1740|work=East Renfrewshire Council official website|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Culture and community==\n\n===Religion===\n[[Image:TBGiffMap1923.jpg|thumb|300px|Map of Giffnock in early 1900s|alt=Map of Giffnock in early 1900s]]\n\nUntil the end of the nineteenth century, Giffnock had no church buildings, and religious meetings took place in the waiting room of Giffnock Railway Station and, later, in the clubhouse at Eastwood Golf Course.<ref name=CAA/> Orchardhill Parish Church, designed by HE Clifford and completed in 1899, was the first church built within Giffnock.<ref name=CAA/> Now a [[Listed building|category B listed building]],<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB5123|desc=Orchardhill Church of Scotland, Church Road, Giffnock|cat=B|access-date=28 March 2019}}</ref> the Church is built in a [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic revival]] style of architecture and is built mainly of locally quarried stone.<ref name=CAA/>\nAlso located in Giffnock is [[Giffnock Synagogue]], founded in 1938 and home to the largest Jewish religious congregation in Scotland.<ref name=Synagogue>{{cite web |title=Synagogue membership in the UK |url=http://www.jpr.org.uk/downloads/Synagogue%20membership.pdf |work=Synagogue membership in the UK |publisher=Institute for Jewish Policy Research |accessdate=20 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60Mnkiz1A?url=http://www.jpr.org.uk/downloads/Synagogue%20membership.pdf |archivedate=22 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Recreation===\nIn 1936 the Tudor Cinema was constructed in Giffnock by Alex Frutin. It opened in December as a \"superb suburban cinema\". The Tudor was an [[Art Deco]] style building and is considered Glasgow's first \"entertainment complex\", featuring a ballroom and restaurant as well as the 2,400-seat cinema.<ref name=STS15>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=15}}</ref>\n\nGiffnock has numerous parks, including [[Rouken Glen]], Huntly Park and Eastwood Park,<ref>[https://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurefirst11438.html Eastwood House] at [[Gazetteer for Scotland]]</ref> where the [[East Renfrewshire Council]] offices are based.<ref>[https://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurefirst11437.html Eastwood Park] at [[Gazetteer for Scotland]]</ref> There remains some ancient woodland in Giffnock, which could be as old as 8,000 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Broadleaved & Mixed Woodland [PDF]|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=951|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:PanoramaGiffnock.jpg|thumb|300px|Panaoramic View of ''Fenwick Road'', the main street in Giffnock.|alt=Panaoramic View of ''Fenwick Road'', the main street in Giffnock]]\nThe lands of Rouken Glen Park originally belonged to the [[The Crown|Scottish Crown]]. Ownership shifted to the [[Earl of Eglinton]] when [[James V of Scotland|James V]] presented the land to [[Hugh Montgomerie, 1st Earl of Eglinton]] on the marriage of his son in 1530.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://personal.cis.strath.ac.uk/~davidm/website/history01.htm |title=History of Rouken Glen |publisher=Personal.cis.strath.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=7 August 2013}}</ref> The area of the estate was farmed until the end of the 18th century and, in 1858, the estate was purchased by local merchant Walter Crum. Alexander Crum inherited the estate in 1879 and is responsible for the layout of Rouken Glen as it is today. On his sudden death in August 1893, the house passed into the hands of his brother, William Graham Crum, who later sold the estate to Archibald Cameron Corbett, MP (later [[Archibald Corbett, 1st Baron Rowallan|Lord Rowallan]]) on 19 May 1905.<ref name=STS22>{{cite book|title=Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.|year=1988|publisher=Eastwood District Libraries|location=[Eastwood]|isbn=1-871215-00-5|page=22}}</ref> In 1906 the estate was given to the City of Glasgow by Lord Rowallan, with the provision that it be for the \"citizens of Glasgow for all time\".<ref name=STS22/> Rouken Glen Park was officially opened on Saturday, 25 May 1906 by Lord Rowallan.<ref name=STS22/>\n\nEastwood Park Leisure Centre has a 25-metre (82&nbsp;ft) swimming pool, two additional smaller pools and two gyms. Activities in the [[leisure centre]] include casual swimming, swimming lessons, pool fun sessions, fitness classes, a sauna and gym sessions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eastwood Park Leisure|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=2203|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>  \n[[Greenbank Garden]], an 18th-century house and garden owned by the [[National Trust for Scotland]], is located between Clarkston and Newton Mearns, near Giffnock. The house has a {{convert|2.5|acre}} [[walled garden]], sixteen rooms and barns and stables. This building is protected as a Category A [[listed building]].<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB18537|desc=Greenbank House, High Flenders Road, by Whitecraigs|cat=A|access-date=28 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n\nThe Giffnock North Social Club, located on Braidbar Road, is a community non-profit making venue run by its members.<ref>[http://www.giffnocknorthsocialclub.co.uk Giffnock North Social Club]</ref> The club host a wide and diverse range of live music events. Faciliies at the club include a lounge and a games room with pool tables, darts and large screen TV. It also has a function hall which can be hired out for special occasions, accommodating up to 150 guests.\n\n=== Sport ===\nIn 1905 the Whitecraigs Golf Club was founded.<ref name=Golf>{{cite web|title=Whitecraigs Golf Club |url=http://www.scotlands-golf-courses.com/index.php?option=com_mtree&task=viewlink&link_id=654 |work=Scotlands Golf Courses |publisher=scotlands-golf-courses.com |accessdate=12 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113161336/http://www.scotlands-golf-courses.com/index.php?option=com_mtree&task=viewlink&link_id=654 |archivedate=13 November 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> The course was originally designed by [[Willie Fernie (golfer)|Willie Fernie]], who was [[The Open Championship]] winner in 1883 and also designed the [[Turnberry (golf course)|Ailsa course at Turnberry]].<ref name=Golf/> Alterations to the course were made in the 1930s by [[James Braid (golfer)|James Braid]], who won [[The Open Championship]] five times between 1901 and 1910.<ref name=Golf/>\n\nMany golfing events have been hosted by the Whitecraigs Golf Club. The club was visited by the United States [[Ryder Cup]] teams of 1929 and 1933. The teams included many golfing legends such as [[Walter Hagen]], [[Gene Sarazen]] and [[Horton Smith]]. Whitecraigs hosted the [[World Senior Championship]] in 1976 and 1978. In 1983, [[Jack Nicklaus]] visited the club to play an exhibition match and run a clinic.\n\n[[Whitecraigs RFC|Whitecraigs Rugby Club]] is a rugby union team based at Newton Mearns, near Giffnock. As of the 2011\u20132012 season, the team competes in the [[Scottish Premiership Division One|Scottish Premiership Division A]].<ref>{{cite web|title=RBS Championship - RBS Championship A |url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/whitecraigs/s/division-6826.html?d_id=5361&page=table |publisher=Whitecraigs Rugby Club |accessdate=15 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233655/http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/whitecraigs/s/division-6826.html?d_id=5361&page=table |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n== Public services ==\nGiffnock forms part of the Western water and sewerage regions of Scotland. [[Waste management]] is provided by the East Renfrewshire local council. Water supplies are provided by [[Scottish Water]], a [[government-owned corporation]] of the [[Scottish Government]]. Giffnock's [[Distribution Network Operator]] for electricity is [[Scottish Power]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.energylinx.co.uk/distribution_network_operators.htm|publisher=energylinx.co.uk|year=2007|accessdate=31 March 2013|title=Electricity Distribution Network Operators|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114055937/http://www.energylinx.co.uk/distribution_network_operators.htm|archivedate=14 January 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[NHS board]] is [[NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde]]. [[Strathclyde Fire and Rescue]] is the [[statutory]] [[Fire services in Scotland|fire and rescue service]]. The nearest fire station is in the neighbouring settlement of [[Clarkston, East Renfrewshire|Clarkston]]<ref>{{cite web |title=East Ayrshire and East Renfrewshire |url=http://www.strathclydefire.org/your-area/e-ayrshire--e-renfrewshire.aspx |publisher=Strathclyde Fire & Rescue |accessdate=31 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921060252/http://www.strathclydefire.org/your-area/e-ayrshire--e-renfrewshire.aspx |archivedate=21 September 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nPolicing in Giffnock is provided by Police Scotland. The [[Strathclyde Partnership for Transport]], a [[Scottish public bodies|public body in Scotland]], has direct operational responsibilities, such as supporting (and in some cases running) local bus services and managing [[integrated ticketing]] in Giffnock and other areas from the former [[Strathclyde]] region.<ref name=\"SPT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spt.co.uk/about/index.html|author=[[Strathclyde Partnership for Transport]]|publisher=spt.co.uk|date=5 September 2007|accessdate=11 February 2008|title=Who we are|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080408063150/http://www.spt.co.uk/about/index.html |archivedate = 8 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Transport Scotland]] manages the local rail network.<ref name=\"SPT\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Gordon Brown]], [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] from 2007\u20132010\n* [[Daniel McGillivray Brown]], chemist \n* [[Aiden McGeady]], Ireland international footballer\n* [[Andrew Robertson]], Scotland international footballer\n* [[Calum Gallagher]], footballer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{Butt-Stations}}\n* Eastwood District Libraries. (1988). ''Sandstone to suburbia : a history of Giffnock.'' {{ISBN|1-871215-00-5}}.\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.scotcities.com/cathcart/eastwood.htm Giffnock & Netherlee illustrated guide] at ''Scotcities''\n\n{{East Renfrewshire}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Towns in East Renfrewshire]]\n[[Category:Greater Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Giffnock| ]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:order main category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giffnock"}
{"title_page": "Capital punishment in Delaware", "text_new": "{{short description|Declared unconstitutional in 2016}}\n'''[[Capital punishment]]''' in '''[[Delaware]]''' was legal prior to it being declared unconstitutional by the [[Delaware Supreme Court]] on August&nbsp;2, 2016.<ref name=\"deonline\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/story/news/local/2016/08/02/court-delawares-death-penalty-law-unconstitutional/87963012/|title=Top court: Delaware's death penalty law unconstitutional|last=Reyes|first=Jessica Masulli|date=2016-08-12|website=Delaware Online|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-03}}</ref> The ruling will retroactively apply to earlier death sentences.<ref>http://www.deathpenaltyinfo.org/node/6629</ref> Today, capital punishment is no longer applied in the state. Despite this ruling, the capital statute for first-degree murder under Title 11, Chapter 42, Section 09 of the Delaware Code has yet to be repealed. \n\nPrior to this, it had the third highest number of executions [[per capita]] behind [[Oklahoma]] and [[Texas]]. 16 people were executed in the state after the ''[[Gregg v. Georgia]]'' decision of 1976.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deathpenaltyinfo.org/state-execution-rates?scid=8&did=477 |title=State Execution Rates  |website=deathpenaltyinfo.org |language=en |access-date=2017-11-24}}</ref> The last person to ever be executed in the state was 28-year-old [[Shannon Johnson (murderer)|Shannon Johnson]], who was executed on April 20, 2012.<ref name=deonline/>\n\n== Former status ==\n===Legal process===\nDelaware was one of the four states, along with [[Capital punishment in Alabama|Alabama]], [[Capital punishment in Florida|Florida]] and [[Capital punishment in Indiana|Indiana]], where the judge may [[Judicial override|override a jury decision]]. The statute was struck down in 2016 because the judge decided not only the sentence itself, but also some factual findings necessary to make the defendant eligible for capital punishment.\n\n[[Governor of Delaware|The Governor]] was allowed to grant a commutation of the death sentence, but only after receiving a Recommendation of Clemency From a Board or Advisory Group. The only [[Furman_v._Georgia|post-Furman]] pardon was granted by Gov. [[Jack Markell]] on January 17, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deathpenaltyinfo.org/article.php?did=126&scid=13 |title=Clemency<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2015-07-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618031902/http://www.deathpenaltyinfo.org/article.php?did=126&scid=13 |archive-date=2008-06-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was the first time the board had recommended a death sentence to be commuted since the reinstatement of capital punishment in 1974.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/18/opinion/a-death-penalty-commutation.html |title= A Death Penalty Commutation |date=2012-01-17 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Capital crimes ===\nMurder was punishable by death when it involved at least one of the following aggravating factors:<ref>Delaware Code \u00a7 4209</ref>\n#The murder was committed by a person in, or who has escaped from, the custody of a law enforcement officer or place of confinement.\n#The murder was committed for the purpose of avoiding or preventing an arrest or for the purpose of effecting an escape from custody.\n#The murder was committed against any [[law enforcement officer]], corrections employee, firefighter, paramedic, emergency medical technician, fire marshal or fire police officer while such victim was engaged in the performance of official duties.\n#The murder was committed against a judicial officer, a former judicial officer, Attorney General, former Attorney General, Assistant or Deputy Attorney General or former Assistant or Deputy Attorney General, State Detective or former State Detective, Special Investigator or former Special Investigator, during, or because of, the exercise of an official duty.\n#The murder was committed against a person who was held or otherwise detained as a shield or [[hostage]].\n#The murder was committed against a person who was held or detained by the defendant for ransom or reward.\n#The murder was committed against a person who was a witness to a crime and who was killed for the purpose of preventing the witness's appearance or testimony in any grand jury, criminal or civil proceeding involving such crime, or in retaliation for the witness's appearance or testimony in any grand jury, criminal or civil proceeding involving such crime.\n#The defendant paid or was paid by another person or had agreed to pay or be paid by another person or had conspired to pay or be paid by another person for the killing of the victim.\n#The defendant was previously convicted of another murder or manslaughter or of a felony involving the use of, or threat of, force or violence upon another person.\n#The murder was committed while the defendant was engaged in the commission of, or attempt to commit, or flight after committing or attempting to commit any degree of rape, unlawful sexual intercourse, arson, kidnapping, robbery, sodomy, burglary, or home invasion.\n#The defendant's course of conduct resulted in the deaths of 2 or more persons where the deaths are a probable consequence of the defendant's conduct.\n#The murder was outrageously or wantonly vile, horrible or inhuman in that it involved torture, depravity of mind, use of an explosive device or poison or the defendant used such means on the victim prior to murdering the victim.\n#The defendant caused or directed another to commit murder or committed murder as an agent or employee of another person.\n#The defendant was under a sentence of life imprisonment, whether for natural life or otherwise, at the time of the commission of the murder.\n#The murder was committed for pecuniary gain.\n#The victim was [[pregnant]].\n#The victim was particularly vulnerable due to a severe intellectual, mental or physical disability.\n#The victim was 62 years of age or older.\n#The victim was a [[child murder|child 14 years of age or younger]], and the murder was committed by an individual who is at least 4 years older than the victim.\n#At the time of the killing, the victim was or had been a nongovernmental informant or had otherwise provided any investigative, law enforcement or police agency with information concerning criminal activity, and the killing was in retaliation for the victim's activities as a nongovernmental informant or in providing information concerning criminal activity to an investigative, law enforcement or police agency.\n#The murder was premeditated and the result of substantial planning. Such planning must be as to the commission of the murder itself and not simply as to the commission or attempted commission of any underlying felony.\n#The murder was committed for the purpose of interfering with the victim's free exercise or enjoyment of any right, privilege or immunity protected by the First Amendment to the United States Constitution, or because the victim has exercised or enjoyed said rights, or because of the victim's race, religion, color, disability, national origin or ancestry.<ref>[http://delcode.delaware.gov/title11/c042/index.shtml]</ref>\n\n===Method===\nOn June 13, 1986, the state adopted [[lethal injection]] as the default method of execution in Delaware. [[Hanging]] was an alternative for those whose offense occurred prior to that date, but in July 2003 no remaining death row inmates were eligible to choose this alternative, and Delaware dismantled its gallows.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deathpenaltyinfo.org/article.php?scid=8&did=245# |title=Methods of Execution<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2015-07-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703193933/http://www.deathpenaltyinfo.org/article.php?scid=8&did=245# |archive-date=2008-07-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe last judicial execution by hanging in the United States was carried out in Delaware on January 25, 1996 against convicted murderer [[Billy Bailey]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1996/01/26/an-execution-in-the-old-way/0fbf3f86-9ecd-4457-bb37-87ffd74018e6/]</ref>\n\n===Death row===\nDelaware's [[death row]] for males was located at the [[James T. Vaughn Correctional Center]] near [[Smyrna, Delaware|Smyrna]]. Female death row prisoners were housed at the Delores J. Baylor Women's Correctional Institution in [[New Castle, Delaware|New Castle]].\n\nThere were 13 inmates on death row when the state Supreme Court invalidated the capital scheme in 2016. All of their sentences were modified, and the last two inmates were resentenced to life in prison in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.delawareonline.com/story/news/local/2018/03/13/delawares-last-death-row-inmates-resentenced-life-prison-tuesday/407863002/ |title=Delaware's last death row inmates resentenced |last=Parra |first=Esteban |website=Delaware online |date=2018-03-13|language=en |access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==Reinstatement bill==\nIn 2017, a bill was proposed by Rep. [[Steve Smyk]] to reinstate the state death penalty.<ref name=\"ChaseDeathPenalty\">{{cite news|last1=Chase|first1=Randall|title=Delaware House postpones vote on reinstating death penalty|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/delaware-house-votes-on-reinstatement-of-death-penalty/2017/05/04/d537b364-30b2-11e7-a335-fa0ae1940305_story.html|accessdate=8 May 2017|publisher=Washington Post|date=4 May 2017}}</ref> The proposal gained support after the murders of police officer [[Stephen Ballard]] and of corrections officer Steven Floyd Sr. in a February 2017 riot at the [[James T. Vaughn Correctional Center]] in [[Smyrna, Delaware]].<ref name=\"AlbrightFirstTest\">{{cite news|last1=Albright|first1=Matthew|title=Delaware death penalty supporters pass first test|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/story/news/politics/2017/05/03/death-penalty-committee/101243632/|accessdate=8 May 2017|publisher=[[The News Journal]]|date=3 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"KelkarUprising\">{{cite news|last1=Kelkar|first1=Kamala|title=Delaware returns to death penalty debate after prison uprising|url=http://sfbayview.com/2017/05/delaware-returns-to-death-penalty-debate-after-prison-uprising/|accessdate=8 May 2017|publisher=[[San Francisco Bay View]]|date=5 May 2017}}</ref> However, the bill failed to get a committee hearing in the Senate. In May 2019, Smyk introduced a similar bill.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://delawarestatenews.net/government/new-legislation-proposes-to-revive-death-penalty-in-delaware/ |title=New legislation proposes to revive death penalty in Delaware |last=Bittle |first=Matt |date=2019-05-15 |website=Delaware State News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of people executed in Delaware]]\n* [[Crime in Delaware]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{CapPun-US}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Capital Punishment in Delaware}}\n[[Category:1974 establishments in Delaware]]\n[[Category:2016 disestablishments in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Capital punishment in Delaware| ]]\n[[Category:Capital punishment in the United States by state|Delaware]]\n[[Category:Delaware law]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Declared unconstitutional in 2016}}\n'''[[Capital punishment]]''' is no longer used in the U.S. state of '''[[Delaware]]'''. The state's capital sentencing scheme was declared unconstitutional by the [[Delaware Supreme Court]] on August&nbsp;2, 2016.<ref name=\"deonline\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/story/news/local/2016/08/02/court-delawares-death-penalty-law-unconstitutional/87963012/|title=Top court: Delaware's death penalty law unconstitutional|last=Reyes|first=Jessica Masulli|date=2016-08-12|website=Delaware Online|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-03}}</ref> The ruling will retroactively apply to earlier death sentences.<ref>http://www.deathpenaltyinfo.org/node/6629</ref> Despite this ruling, the capital statute for first-degree murder under Title 11, Chapter 42, Section 09 of the Delaware Code has yet to be repealed. \n\nPrior to this, it had the third highest number of executions [[per capita]] behind [[Oklahoma]] and [[Texas]]. 16 people were executed in the state after the ''[[Gregg v. Georgia]]'' decision of 1976.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deathpenaltyinfo.org/state-execution-rates?scid=8&did=477 |title=State Execution Rates  |website=deathpenaltyinfo.org |language=en |access-date=2017-11-24}}</ref> The last person to ever be executed in the state was 28-year-old [[Shannon Johnson (murderer)|Shannon Johnson]], who was executed on April 20, 2012.<ref name=deonline/>\n\n== Former status ==\n===Legal process===\nDelaware was one of the four states, along with [[Capital punishment in Alabama|Alabama]], [[Capital punishment in Florida|Florida]] and [[Capital punishment in Indiana|Indiana]], where the judge may [[Judicial override|override a jury decision]]. The statute was struck down in 2016 because the judge decided not only the sentence itself, but also some factual findings necessary to make the defendant eligible for capital punishment.\n\n[[Governor of Delaware|The Governor]] was allowed to grant a commutation of the death sentence, but only after receiving a Recommendation of Clemency From a Board or Advisory Group. The only [[Furman_v._Georgia|post-Furman]] pardon was granted by Gov. [[Jack Markell]] on January 17, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deathpenaltyinfo.org/article.php?did=126&scid=13 |title=Clemency<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2015-07-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618031902/http://www.deathpenaltyinfo.org/article.php?did=126&scid=13 |archive-date=2008-06-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was the first time the board had recommended a death sentence to be commuted since the reinstatement of capital punishment in 1974.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/18/opinion/a-death-penalty-commutation.html |title= A Death Penalty Commutation |date=2012-01-17 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Capital crimes ===\nMurder was punishable by death when it involved at least one of the following aggravating factors:<ref>Delaware Code \u00a7 4209</ref>\n#The murder was committed by a person in, or who has escaped from, the custody of a law enforcement officer or place of confinement.\n#The murder was committed for the purpose of avoiding or preventing an arrest or for the purpose of effecting an escape from custody.\n#The murder was committed against any [[law enforcement officer]], corrections employee, firefighter, paramedic, emergency medical technician, fire marshal or fire police officer while such victim was engaged in the performance of official duties.\n#The murder was committed against a judicial officer, a former judicial officer, Attorney General, former Attorney General, Assistant or Deputy Attorney General or former Assistant or Deputy Attorney General, State Detective or former State Detective, Special Investigator or former Special Investigator, during, or because of, the exercise of an official duty.\n#The murder was committed against a person who was held or otherwise detained as a shield or [[hostage]].\n#The murder was committed against a person who was held or detained by the defendant for ransom or reward.\n#The murder was committed against a person who was a witness to a crime and who was killed for the purpose of preventing the witness's appearance or testimony in any grand jury, criminal or civil proceeding involving such crime, or in retaliation for the witness's appearance or testimony in any grand jury, criminal or civil proceeding involving such crime.\n#The defendant paid or was paid by another person or had agreed to pay or be paid by another person or had conspired to pay or be paid by another person for the killing of the victim.\n#The defendant was previously convicted of another murder or manslaughter or of a felony involving the use of, or threat of, force or violence upon another person.\n#The murder was committed while the defendant was engaged in the commission of, or attempt to commit, or flight after committing or attempting to commit any degree of rape, unlawful sexual intercourse, arson, kidnapping, robbery, sodomy, burglary, or home invasion.\n#The defendant's course of conduct resulted in the deaths of 2 or more persons where the deaths are a probable consequence of the defendant's conduct.\n#The murder was outrageously or wantonly vile, horrible or inhuman in that it involved torture, depravity of mind, use of an explosive device or poison or the defendant used such means on the victim prior to murdering the victim.\n#The defendant caused or directed another to commit murder or committed murder as an agent or employee of another person.\n#The defendant was under a sentence of life imprisonment, whether for natural life or otherwise, at the time of the commission of the murder.\n#The murder was committed for pecuniary gain.\n#The victim was [[pregnant]].\n#The victim was particularly vulnerable due to a severe intellectual, mental or physical disability.\n#The victim was 62 years of age or older.\n#The victim was a [[child murder|child 14 years of age or younger]], and the murder was committed by an individual who is at least 4 years older than the victim.\n#At the time of the killing, the victim was or had been a nongovernmental informant or had otherwise provided any investigative, law enforcement or police agency with information concerning criminal activity, and the killing was in retaliation for the victim's activities as a nongovernmental informant or in providing information concerning criminal activity to an investigative, law enforcement or police agency.\n#The murder was premeditated and the result of substantial planning. Such planning must be as to the commission of the murder itself and not simply as to the commission or attempted commission of any underlying felony.\n#The murder was committed for the purpose of interfering with the victim's free exercise or enjoyment of any right, privilege or immunity protected by the First Amendment to the United States Constitution, or because the victim has exercised or enjoyed said rights, or because of the victim's race, religion, color, disability, national origin or ancestry.<ref>[http://delcode.delaware.gov/title11/c042/index.shtml]</ref>\n\n===Method===\nOn June 13, 1986, the state adopted [[lethal injection]] as the default method of execution in Delaware. [[Hanging]] was an alternative for those whose offense occurred prior to that date, but in July 2003 no remaining death row inmates were eligible to choose this alternative, and Delaware dismantled its gallows.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deathpenaltyinfo.org/article.php?scid=8&did=245# |title=Methods of Execution<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2015-07-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703193933/http://www.deathpenaltyinfo.org/article.php?scid=8&did=245# |archive-date=2008-07-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe last judicial execution by hanging in the United States was carried out in Delaware on January 25, 1996 against convicted murderer [[Billy Bailey]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1996/01/26/an-execution-in-the-old-way/0fbf3f86-9ecd-4457-bb37-87ffd74018e6/]</ref>\n\n===Death row===\nDelaware's [[death row]] for males was located at the [[James T. Vaughn Correctional Center]] near [[Smyrna, Delaware|Smyrna]]. Female death row prisoners were housed at the Delores J. Baylor Women's Correctional Institution in [[New Castle, Delaware|New Castle]].\n\nThere were 13 inmates on death row when the state Supreme Court invalidated the capital scheme in 2016. All of their sentences were modified, and the last two inmates were resentenced to life in prison in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.delawareonline.com/story/news/local/2018/03/13/delawares-last-death-row-inmates-resentenced-life-prison-tuesday/407863002/ |title=Delaware's last death row inmates resentenced |last=Parra |first=Esteban |website=Delaware online |date=2018-03-13|language=en |access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==Reinstatement bill==\nIn 2017, a bill was proposed by Rep. [[Steve Smyk]] to reinstate the state death penalty.<ref name=\"ChaseDeathPenalty\">{{cite news|last1=Chase|first1=Randall|title=Delaware House postpones vote on reinstating death penalty|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/delaware-house-votes-on-reinstatement-of-death-penalty/2017/05/04/d537b364-30b2-11e7-a335-fa0ae1940305_story.html|accessdate=8 May 2017|publisher=Washington Post|date=4 May 2017}}</ref> The proposal gained support after the murders of police officer [[Stephen Ballard]] and of corrections officer Steven Floyd Sr. in a February 2017 riot at the [[James T. Vaughn Correctional Center]] in [[Smyrna, Delaware]].<ref name=\"AlbrightFirstTest\">{{cite news|last1=Albright|first1=Matthew|title=Delaware death penalty supporters pass first test|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/story/news/politics/2017/05/03/death-penalty-committee/101243632/|accessdate=8 May 2017|publisher=[[The News Journal]]|date=3 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"KelkarUprising\">{{cite news|last1=Kelkar|first1=Kamala|title=Delaware returns to death penalty debate after prison uprising|url=http://sfbayview.com/2017/05/delaware-returns-to-death-penalty-debate-after-prison-uprising/|accessdate=8 May 2017|publisher=[[San Francisco Bay View]]|date=5 May 2017}}</ref> However, the bill failed to get a committee hearing in the Senate. In May 2019, Smyk introduced a similar bill.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://delawarestatenews.net/government/new-legislation-proposes-to-revive-death-penalty-in-delaware/ |title=New legislation proposes to revive death penalty in Delaware |last=Bittle |first=Matt |date=2019-05-15 |website=Delaware State News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of people executed in Delaware]]\n* [[Crime in Delaware]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{CapPun-US}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Capital Punishment in Delaware}}\n[[Category:1974 establishments in Delaware]]\n[[Category:2016 disestablishments in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Capital punishment in Delaware| ]]\n[[Category:Capital punishment in the United States by state|Delaware]]\n[[Category:Delaware law]]\n", "name_user": "ZG1996", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_punishment_in_Delaware"}
{"title_page": "Hard to Handle (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1968 song by Otis Redding}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Hard to Handle\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[Otis Redding]]\n| album    = [[The Immortal Otis Redding]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| released = June 1968\n| format   =\n| recorded = 1967\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Soul music|Soul]]\n| length   = 2:17\n| label    = [[Atco Records|Atco]]\n| writer   = [[Allen Jones (record producer)|Allen Jones]], [[Al Bell]], and [[Otis Redding]]\n| producer = [[Steve Cropper]]\n}}\n\n'''\"Hard to Handle\"''' is a 1968 song written by [[United States|American]] [[soul music|soul]] star [[Otis Redding]] along with [[Al Bell]] and [[Allen Jones (record producer)|Allen Jones]]. Originally recorded by Redding, it was released in 1968 as the B-side to \"[[Amen (gospel song)|Amen]]\" (shortly after the singer's sudden death in 1967). The song also appears on the 1968 album ''[[The Immortal Otis Redding]]''. Redding's version reached #38 on the Billboard R&B charts and #51 on the pop charts.\n\nNumerous [[Cover (music)|covers]] of the song exist, most notably a 1990 [[blues rock]] take on the track by band [[The Black Crowes]].\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Hard to Handle\n| cover      = HardtoHandle.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Black Crowes]]\n| album      = [[Shake Your Money Maker (album)|Shake Your Money Maker]]\n| released   = 1990\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1989\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]], [[blues rock]]\n| length     = 3:08\n| label      = [[American Recordings (US)|Def American]]\n| writer     = [[Allen Jones (record producer)|Allen Jones]], [[Al Bell]], and [[Otis Redding]]\n| producer   = [[George Drakoulias]]\n| prev_title = [[Jealous Again (The Black Crowes song)|Jealous Again]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = [[Twice As Hard]]\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{cleanup|section|reason=covers may not meet [[WP:SONGCOVER]]|date=January 2019}}\nThe song has been covered by many artists, including [[Patti Drew]] (with perhaps the earliest cover in 1968), [[King Floyd]], [[Grateful Dead]], [[The Black Crowes]], [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]], [[Toots and the Maytals]], [[Rustix]], [[Band from TV]], [[Harpers Bizarre]], [[Gov't Mule]], [[Tony Joe White]], [[Magic Slim and the Teardrops]], [[New Riders of the Purple Sage]], [[Matt Giraud]], [[Etta James]] and [[Snafu (band)|Snafu]] as well as by [[Mae West]] in the film ''[[Myra Breckinridge (film)|Myra Breckinridge]]''. It was covered by the band [[Liquid Smoke]] in 1969 in a style very similar to The Black Crowes version.\n\n* \"Hard to Handle\" was a mainstay of the [[Grateful Dead]]'s live set from 1969 to 1971, as sung by [[Ron \"Pigpen\" McKernan]]. [[Etta James]] joined the [[Grateful Dead]] for their 12-31-1982 New Years show and they performed it together. The song has been played by [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]], [[Bob Weir]] and [[Phil Lesh and Friends]].\n* The [[Stanford Band]] performs a cover as part of their standard repertoire. A recording is on their album ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090601122346/http://lsjumb.stanford.edu/about/albums/5/ The Wind of Freedom Blow (Greatest Hits 1970-1998)]''.\n* [[Gov't Mule]] with [[Toots Hibbert]] covered the song on Gov't Mule's 2006 album, ''[[Mighty High]]''.\n* In August 2007, soul singer [[Guy Sebastian]] recorded a tribute version of \"Hard to Handle\" at [[Ardent Studios]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], for his album of soul classics, ''[[The Memphis Album]]'' with many of the original [[Stax Records|Stax]] music band members including [[Steve Cropper]], [[Donald \"Duck\" Dunn]], Lester Snell, and [[Booker T. & the M.G.'s#Members|Steve Potts]].\n* ''[[American Idol]]'' contestant [[Phillip Phillips]] performed the song on the [[American Idol (season 11)|eleventh season]] of the show. The studio version is available for download on iTunes.\n\n===The Black Crowes version===\nPerhaps the most notable cover is by [[The Black Crowes]], for whom it was a breakout hit single from their 1990 debut album ''[[Shake Your Money Maker (album)|Shake Your Money Maker]]''.  Two versions of the song exist: the original album version and the hit single remixed with an overdubbed brass section. {{cn|date=July 2015}} The Crowes' version reached number one on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Album Rock Tracks]] chart and number 26 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\nA cover version in the style of the Black Crowes is available as a downloadable track for the [[music video game]] series ''[[Rock Band (series)|Rock Band]]''. Another covered version by [[Steve Ouimette]] is in the video game ''[[Guitar Hero: Aerosmith]]''.\n\n====Charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1990\u20131991)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|title=Australia's Music Charts 1988\u20132010|year=2011|publisher=Moonlight Publishing|location=Mt. Martha, VIC, Australia}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|79\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|40|chartid=9091|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|56|artist=The Black Crowes|song=Hard to Handle|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}\n|-\n|Poland ([[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://lp3.polskieradio.pl/notowania/?numer=512|title=Notowanie nr512|publisher=[[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]]|language=Polish|date=December 13, 1991|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|45\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|45|date=19900922|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|26|artist=The Black Crowes|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardmainstreamrock|1|artist=The Black Crowes|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}\n|}\n\n==Other uses==\n* Reggae artist [[Capleton]] used the ascension / descension for \"Wings of the Mourning\" (remix) 1992 on the Def Jam label [[Masta Ace]] samples this song's bass line for \"Four Minus Three\", a song from his debut album ''[[Take a Look Around (album)|Take a Look Around]]''.\n* The [[Lemon Jelly]] 2001 song \"[[Soft/Rock|Rock]]\", from a rare limited edition (1000 copies) single called \"[[Soft/Rock]]\" (which came in a pair of [[Levi Strauss & Co.|Levi's]] jeans with a condom in the pocket), features sampled elements of \"Hard to Handle\".\n* The hip-hop producer [[Marley Marl]] sampled the five-note ascension and descension intro for his song \"The Symphony\" from his 1988 album ''[[In Control, Volume 1]]''. This was re-sampled for the 1992 [[Wreckx-N-Effect]] song \"Hard\" and the 1999 [[Snoop Dogg]] song \"Ghetto Symphony\" from his 1999 album ''[[No Limit Top Dogg]]''. \n* Rapper [[Frankie Cutlass]] also uses the five ascending notes{{what|date=September 2017}} on his song \"The Cypher Pt III\" from his 1997 album ''[[Politics & Bullshit|Politics & Bullsh*t]]''.\n* German hip-hop band [[F\u00fcnf Sterne deluxe]] used the melody and samples in their 1998 song \"Willst du mit mir gehn\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|black-crowes|hard-to-handle}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{TheBlackCrowes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hard To Handle}}\n[[Category:1968 singles]]\n[[Category:1990 singles]]\n[[Category:American Recordings (record label) singles]]\n[[Category:Otis Redding songs]]\n[[Category:Grateful Dead songs]]\n[[Category:The Black Crowes songs]]\n[[Category:Tony Joe White songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs released posthumously]]\n[[Category:Guy Sebastian songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Otis Redding]]\n[[Category:1968 songs]]\n[[Category:Atco Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1968 song by Otis Redding}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Hard to Handle\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[Otis Redding]]\n| album    = [[The Immortal Otis Redding]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| released = June 1968\n| format   =\n| recorded = 1967\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Soul music|Soul]]\n| length   = 2:17\n| label    = [[Atco Records|Atco]]\n| writer   = [[Allen Jones (record producer)|Allen Jones]], [[Al Bell]], and [[Otis Redding]]\n| producer = [[Steve Cropper]]\n}}\n\n'''\"Hard to Handle\"''' is a 1968 song written by [[United States|American]] [[soul music|soul]] star [[Otis Redding]] along with [[Al Bell]] and [[Allen Jones (record producer)|Allen Jones]]. Originally recorded by Redding, it was released in 1968 as the B-side to \"[[Amen (gospel song)|Amen]]\" (shortly after the singer's sudden death in 1967). The song also appears on the 1968 album ''[[The Immortal Otis Redding]]''. Redding's version reached #38 on the Billboard R&B charts and #51 on the pop charts.\n\nNumerous [[Cover (music)|covers]] of the song exist, most notably a 1990 [[blues rock]] take on the track by band [[The Black Crowes]].\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Hard to Handle\n| cover      = HardtoHandle.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Black Crowes]]\n| album      = [[Shake Your Money Maker (album)|Shake Your Money Maker]]\n| released   = 1990\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1989\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]], [[blues rock]]\n| length     = 3:08\n| label      = [[American Recordings (US)|Def American]]\n| writer     = [[Allen Jones (record producer)|Allen Jones]], [[Al Bell]], and [[Otis Redding]]\n| producer   = [[George Drakoulias]]\n| prev_title = [[Jealous Again (The Black Crowes song)|Jealous Again]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = [[Twice As Hard]]\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{cleanup|section|reason=covers may not meet [[WP:SONGCOVER]]|date=January 2019}}\nThe song has been covered by many artists, including [[Patti Drew]] (with perhaps the earliest cover in 1968), [[King Floyd]], [[Grateful Dead]], [[The Black Crowes]], [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]], [[Toots and the Maytals]], [[Rustix]], [[Band from TV]], [[Harpers Bizarre]], [[Gov't Mule]], [[Tony Joe White]], [[Magic Slim and the Teardrops]], [[New Riders of the Purple Sage]], [[Matt Giraud]], [[Etta James]] and [[Snafu (band)|Snafu]] as well as by [[Mae West]] in the film ''[[Myra Breckinridge (film)|Myra Breckinridge]]''. It was covered by the band [[Liquid Smoke]] in 1969 in a style very similar to The Black Crowes version.\n\n* \"Hard to Handle\" was a mainstay of the [[Grateful Dead]]'s live set from 1969 to 1971, as sung by [[Ron \"Pigpen\" McKernan]]. [[Etta James]] joined the [[Grateful Dead]] for their 12-31-1982 New Years show and they performed it together. The song has been played by [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]], [[Bob Weir]] and [[Phil Lesh and Friends]].\n* The [[Stanford Band]] performs a cover as part of their standard repertoire. A recording is on their album ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090601122346/http://lsjumb.stanford.edu/about/albums/5/ The Wind of Freedom Blow (Greatest Hits 1970-1998)]''.\n* [[Gov't Mule]] with [[Toots Hibbert]] covered the song on Gov't Mule's 2006 album, ''[[Mighty High]]''.\n* In August 2007, soul singer [[Guy Sebastian]] recorded a tribute version of \"Hard to Handle\" at [[Ardent Studios]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], for his album of soul classics, ''[[The Memphis Album]]'' with many of the original [[Stax Records|Stax]] music band members including [[Steve Cropper]], [[Donald \"Duck\" Dunn]], Lester Snell, and [[Booker T. & the M.G.'s#Members|Steve Potts]].\n* ''[[American Idol]]'' contestant [[Phillip Phillips]] performed the song on the [[American Idol (season 11)|eleventh season]] of the show. The studio version is available for download on iTunes.\n\n===The Black Crowes version===\nPerhaps the most notable cover is by [[The Black Crowes]], for whom it was a breakout hit single from their 1990 debut album ''[[Shake Your Money Maker (album)|Shake Your Money Maker]]''.  Two versions of the song exist: the original album version and the hit single remixed with an overdubbed brass section. {{cn|date=July 2015}} The Crowes' version reached number one on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Album Rock Tracks]] chart and number 26 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\nA cover version in the style of the Black Crowes is available as a downloadable track for the [[music video game]] series ''[[Rock Band (series)|Rock Band]]''. Another covered version by [[Steve Ouimette]] is in the video game ''[[Guitar Hero: Aerosmith]]''.\n\n====Charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1990\u20131991)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|title=Australia's Music Charts 1988\u20132010|year=2011|publisher=Moonlight Publishing|location=Mt. Martha, VIC, Australia}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|79\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|40|chartid=9091|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|56|artist=The Black Crowes|song=Hard to Handle|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}\n|-\n|Poland ([[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://lp3.polskieradio.pl/notowania/?numer=512|title=Notowanie nr512|publisher=[[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]]|language=Polish|date=December 13, 1991|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|45\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|45|date=19900922|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|26|artist=The Black Crowes|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardmainstreamrock|1|artist=The Black Crowes|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}\n|}\n\n==Other uses==\n* Reggae artist [[Capleton]] used the ascension / descension for \"Wings of the Mourning\" (remix) 1992 on the Def Jam label [[Masta Ace]] samples this song's bass line for \"Four Minus Three\", a song from his debut album ''[[Take a Look Around (album)|Take a Look Around]]''.\n* The [[Lemon Jelly]] 2001 song \"[[Soft/Rock|Rock]]\", from a rare limited edition (1000 copies) single called \"[[Soft/Rock]]\" (which came in a pair of [[Levi Strauss & Co.|Levi's]] jeans with a condom in the pocket), features sampled elements of \"Hard to Handle\".\n* The hip-hop producer [[Marley Marl]] sampled the five-note ascension and descension intro for his song \"The Symphony\" from his 1988 album ''[[In Control, Volume 1]]''. This was re-sampled for the 1992 [[Wreckx-N-Effect]] song \"Hard\" and the 1999 [[Snoop Dogg]] song \"Ghetto Symphony\" from his 1999 album ''[[No Limit Top Dogg]]''. \n* Rapper [[Frankie Cutlass]] also uses the five ascending notes{{what|date=September 2017}} on his song \"The Cypher Pt III\" from his 1997 album ''[[Politics & Bullshit|Politics & Bullsh*t]]''.\n* Germnan hip-hop band [[F\u00fcnf Sterne deluxe]] used the melody and samples in their 1998 song \"Willst du mit mir gehn\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|black-crowes|hard-to-handle}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{TheBlackCrowes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hard To Handle}}\n[[Category:1968 singles]]\n[[Category:1990 singles]]\n[[Category:American Recordings (record label) singles]]\n[[Category:Otis Redding songs]]\n[[Category:Grateful Dead songs]]\n[[Category:The Black Crowes songs]]\n[[Category:Tony Joe White songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs released posthumously]]\n[[Category:Guy Sebastian songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Otis Redding]]\n[[Category:1968 songs]]\n[[Category:Atco Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Jpazol", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hard_to_Handle_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Samoa", "text_new": "{{Short description|Country in the Central Pacific Ocean}}\n{{about|the nation of Samoa|the geographical region|Samoan Islands|the Samoan United States territory|American Samoa|other uses}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Coord|13|35|S|172|20|W|display=title}}\n\n{{Infobox country\n| conventional_long_name                = Independent State of Samoa\n| common_name                = Samoa\n| native_name                = {{native name|sm|Malo Sa{{okina}}oloto Tuto{{okina}}atasi o S\u0101moa<wbr />}}\n| image_flag                = Flag of Samoa.svg\n| image_coat                = Coat of arms of Samoa.svg\n| symbol_type                = Coat of arms\n| national_motto                = \"Fa\u02bbavae i le [[Atua]] S\u0101moa\"<br />{{small|\"Samoa is founded on God\"}}\n| national_anthem                = ''[[The Banner of Freedom|O le fu\u02bba o le sa\u02bbolotoga o Samoa]]''<br />{{small|\"The Banner of Freedom\"}}\n| image_map                = Samoa on the globe (Polynesia centered).svg\n| image_map2                = Samoa - Location Map (2013) - WSM - UNOCHA.svg\n| capital                = [[Apia]]\n| coordinates                = {{Coord|13|50|S|171|45|W|type:city}}\n| largest_city                = Apia\n| official_languages                = {{unbulleted list |[[English language|English]]|[[Samoan language|Samoan]]}}\n| religion                = [[Christianity]] ([[#Religion|official]])<ref name=\"Religion\"/>\n| ethnic_groups                = {{unbulleted list\n  |  92.6% [[Samoans]]\n  |  7.0% [[Euronesian]]s\n  |  0.4% [[Europeans]]\n  |  0.1% [[East Asian]]<ref name=cia>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ws.html |title=Samoa |work=CIA \u2013 The World Factbook}}</ref>\n }}\n| ethnic_groups_year                = 2001\n| demonym                = [[Samoans|Samoan]]\n| government_type                = [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Dominant-party system|dominant-party]] [[parliamentary republic]]<!--- Consensus in the talk page states that Samoa is a Republic.--->\n| leader_title1                = [[O le Ao o le Malo]]\n| leader_name1                = [[Va'aletoa Sualauvi II]]<sup>a</sup>\n| leader_title2                = [[Prime Minister of Samoa|Prime Minister]]\n| leader_name2                = [[Tuilaepa Aiono Sailele Malielegaoi]]\n| leader_title3                = [[Legislative Assembly|Assembly Speaker]]\n| leader_name3                = [[Toleafoa Faafisi]]\n| legislature                = [[Legislative Assembly of Samoa|Legislative Assembly]]\n| sovereignty_type                = Independence from [[New Zealand]]\n| established_event1                = [[Treaty of Berlin (1889)|Treaty of Berlin]]\n| established_date1                = 14 June 1889\n| established_event2                = [[Tripartite Convention]]\n| established_date2                = 16 February 1900\n| established_event3                = [[German Samoa|Colonisation by Germany]]\n| established_date3                = 1 March 1900\n| established_event4                = [[Western Samoa Trust Territory|Colonisation by New Zealand]]\n| established_date4                = 30 August 1914\n| established_event5                = League mandate\n| established_date5                = 17 December 1920\n| established_event6                = UN trusteeship\n| established_date6                = 13 December 1946\n| established_event7                = Western Samoa Act 1961\n| established_date7                = 1 January 1962\n| established_event8                = [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 399|Admitted to the]] [[United Nations]]\n| established_date8                = 15 December 1976\n| area_km2                = 2,842\n| area_rank                = 167th <!-- Area rank should match [[List of countries and dependencies by area]] -->\n| area_sq_mi                = 1097\n| percent_water                = 0.3\n| population_